[Amit Varma]: l, Storytel.com. Shambhavi, welcome to the scene in the unseen.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:24.440
[Guest]: Thanks, Amit. It's great to be here. I feel I've unlocked an achievement.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Oh my God. Just by being on the show.

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And also on the soundcheck, when I asked you for the soundcheck before we just started,

00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:33.360
[Guest]: you were saying, Hi, I'm Yazad. Kindly explain.

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:37.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know Yazad very well. Yazad was also part of Takshashila.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:39.600
[Guest]: And he's been on my show a couple of times.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:45.160
[Guest]: So when we first started doing our daily podcast, Yazad and I were co-hosts, and this was supposed

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:49.800
[Guest]: to be a mic check. Hi, I'm Yazad. Hi, I'm Yazad. And they just caught on. So at Takshashila,

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:54.680
[Amit Varma]: Hi, I'm Yazad is what we say for mic checks. So, Hi, Yazad.

00:04:54.680 --> 00:04:59.400
[Amit Varma]: Hi, Yazad. All roads lead to Yazad indeed. Okay, so you know, before we kind of get to

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:04.000
[Amit Varma]: the very serious subject at hand, tell me a bit about yourself. I mean, I don't know

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.240
[Amit Varma]: you very well. But in the little time that we've interacted, what has been very clear

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:12.080
[Amit Varma]: to me is that you are like super passionate about science, in the same way that you know,

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:15.840
[Amit Varma]: other people are about books and movies, and they'll discuss the Marvel Universe and all

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:19.960
[Amit Varma]: of that. And you are into science in that way. You're not someone who, you know, happened

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:24.560
[Amit Varma]: to do her education and then just kind of went along with that. Tell me a little bit

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:29.080
[Amit Varma]: about this love for science. And, you know, were you always going to be a serious scientist

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:31.240
[Amit Varma]: like you are? Or you know, how did that all that happen?

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:35.840
[Guest]: No, I mean, currently, I'm fascinated by science. Even though I have now moved away from doing

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:40.600
[Guest]: wet lab research, I now focus more on the policy aspects of science. But still, it's

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:44.920
[Guest]: just, it's what keeps me up at night, you know, a new paper that has come out, or a

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:50.360
[Guest]: new technique that we learn, I love reading about it. When I started out, born into a

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:56.280
[Guest]: middle class Maharashtrian family, I was told I was going to be a doctor, it was predestined.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:59.760
[Guest]: I think my parents decided that the day I was born, this one is going to be a doctor,

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:04.040
[Guest]: my brother's an engineer, so obviously, and I lost my grandmother when I was eight. She

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:07.880
[Guest]: passed away because of breast cancer, which spread to her lung. So I decided that was

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:12.680
[Guest]: it, I was going to be a doctor, I was going to cure cancer, and I was going to be like

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:16.920
[Guest]: this, win the Nobel Prize, eventually, you know, all of that. I always envisioned myself

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:20.560
[Guest]: walking down the street and this kid comes running to me who says, Oh, you saved my grandmother,

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:24.280
[Guest]: thank you. And that would be redemption. That was the environment I grew up into. Actually

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:30.080
[Guest]: thought I was going to be a doctor till I passed my 12th exam, and this was in Mumbai.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:34.120
[Guest]: And I did not get enough marks to get into a good medical college. My parents thought

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:39.600
[Guest]: that they could still fund me to go into somewhere which was decent enough. And I made a choice

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.800
[Guest]: that I did not want that kind of education. I did not want to be that kind of liability

00:06:43.800 --> 00:06:49.000
[Guest]: on anybody. And so I instead went and did my BSc at Ruia College. And going to BSc,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.960
[Guest]: I think was a little risky then, it was not supposed to be the honourable thing to do.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:58.160
[Guest]: I did not know I was going to do a PhD afterwards. But I really truly enjoyed that experience.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:03.200
[Guest]: Because that's where I met science for the first time. I wasn't being taught science

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.360
[Guest]: anymore, I could explore, I could go to go and sit in a library, and just learn about

00:07:07.360 --> 00:07:12.880
[Guest]: genetics and biology. And I was just completely like taken in orbit. And I decided I wanted

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:17.600
[Guest]: to continue in basic science. It was also the first time that I realised that doctors

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:22.640
[Guest]: don't cure diseases, they treat diseases. And as a scientist to figure out how diseases

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:27.640
[Guest]: are caused and can actually come up with the cures for them. I was not saying doctors can't,

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:32.720
[Guest]: but they are so engrossed in their day to day stuff. So that was when I realised that

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:38.720
[Guest]: maybe doing a PhD in cancer biology would allow me that option to come up with diagnostics

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:42.600
[Guest]: or therapeutics or whatever I wanted to do. So that's how I stayed in science. It was

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:50.640
[Guest]: actually completely out of the love for understanding how life has evolved, how life works. And

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:56.980
[Guest]: the DNA is just an elegant, beautiful structure. And the fact that you can encode for everything

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:59.320
[Guest]: under the sun is simply marvellous.

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:04.840
[Amit Varma]: I remember Douglas Adams, who I quoted in my introduction, was once asked why he didn't

00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:08.600
[Amit Varma]: believe in God. And he said he didn't believe in God because of natural selection. And he

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:13.280
[Amit Varma]: said that just understanding that theory and what it meant filled him with so much awe

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:17.640
[Amit Varma]: that no divine awe could, you know, compare with something like that. So where did you

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:18.960
[Guest]: go to do your PhD?

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:23.520
[Guest]: I went to the University of Leicester in the UK. So I went to do my master's and that was

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:28.840
[Guest]: I decided, obviously, pre-decided when I was eight, that cancer biology was what it was

00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:33.760
[Guest]: going to be. And University of Leicester was one of the few places that offered a master's

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:41.260
[Guest]: in cancer cell and molecular biology. So I went to the UK. I was allowed to stay back

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:46.280
[Guest]: in the lab to do a PhD as well. So the university actually gave me a scholarship. So I finished

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:51.600
[Guest]: my master's, my PhD and a year's worth of postdoc in that same lab. And then I moved

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:56.280
[Guest]: to the National Centre for Biological Sciences here in Bangalore, where I did my postdoc

00:08:56.280 --> 00:09:00.760
[Guest]: again, looking at breast cancer. This was all very lucky that I actually got to work

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:06.320
[Guest]: in breast cancer that easily. So I did spend about nine years closely examining the pathways

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:09.520
[Guest]: that cause cancer to be formed.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:15.320
[Amit Varma]: And two questions really. And when did you get interested in genetics per se, as a sort

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:21.320
[Amit Varma]: of a subset of whatever you were working on? And also, how did you then move away from,

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:25.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, doing science to, you know, into the policy space and being an entrepreneur?

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:30.680
[Guest]: So, genetics has been something that has always, I mean, as I said, and I think this is the

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:36.240
[Guest]: third time I'm using this word, fascinated by. It is just that the small molecule that

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:42.520
[Guest]: can do so much and has survived the test of time for so long. And obviously, it goes wrong

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:49.560
[Guest]: in so many ways in cancer. It is phenomenal. I mean, you spoke about humans being a puddle.

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:56.400
[Guest]: I look at humans as a cancer. We have a lot of characteristics of cancers among us, right?

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:02.040
[Guest]: We divide nonstop. We change the microenvironment around us to suit us, and we end up destroying

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:06.840
[Guest]: everything apart from that. And if we are not careful now, we might actually end up

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:12.640
[Guest]: killing the person, killing the ecosystem that hosts us. That, I think, is something

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:18.360
[Guest]: about that we have a lot of lessons to learn from genetics that we can adapt and use. And

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:25.560
[Guest]: if we are intelligent enough, hopefully, learn from to change our behaviour now. So, I have

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:30.600
[Guest]: always been in love with genetics. It's just that it's micro level of doing things and

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:34.160
[Guest]: things work so well. I mean, things could go wrong and having a baby, right, things

00:10:34.160 --> 00:10:38.280
[Guest]: could go wrong at so many levels, but they don't always. And you sometimes get this really

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:42.840
[Guest]: complicated being come out of your bodies. I still don't understand how it works. It's

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:43.840
[Guest]: superb.

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:48.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that's one of the remarkable things about it that it's so incredibly complicated

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:54.520
[Amit Varma]: is far more complicated than any process we've designed. And yet we have this bias towards

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:59.600
[Amit Varma]: thinking that everything necessarily needs a designer or needs to be planned or engineered

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:05.480
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. And actually, what is happening in, you know, what has happened in nature,

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:10.400
[Amit Varma]: natural selection is a kind of spontaneous order. All of this design has sort of happened

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:15.960
[Amit Varma]: by itself and is way more complex than anything, any designer, even a divine one. And of course,

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:16.960
[Amit Varma]: she doesn't exist.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:21.680
[Guest]: I think we're lucky for that. Because I think if a designer had to design what the DNA does,

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:26.680
[Guest]: you might end up with a really complicated, huge, big entity, and not the small, elegant

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:31.160
[Guest]: stuff that we have ended up with. We might have been bulky and huge. But yeah, because

00:11:31.160 --> 00:11:32.680
[Amit Varma]: it has come out the way it has.

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:37.200
[Amit Varma]: I've been off my keto diet for a long time. So, I am still bulky and huge. And the second

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.680
[Amit Varma]: question. So, you know, you're doing science, it's obviously clearly something you're in

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:45.320
[Amit Varma]: love with. How do you then, you know, move into being a policy person, being an entrepreneur?

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:50.840
[Guest]: So, I was in the UK for nearly six years. And then I was in Bangalore for three years,

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:56.440
[Guest]: working on more or less the same themes. But there were two problems which were very acutely

00:11:56.440 --> 00:12:02.600
[Guest]: I became aware of the moment I started working in the lab here. One is that supplies for

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:07.280
[Guest]: any lab experiment that we do takes a huge amount of time to come to India. So, when

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:11.040
[Guest]: I was in the UK, and if I ordered something, it would come in like two or three days, any

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:16.800
[Guest]: glassware, enzyme, whatever I needed. Here, it takes two or three weeks. And that, at

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:20.840
[Guest]: the core of it, is a data asymmetry problem. Labs don't know which suppliers to reach out

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:26.200
[Guest]: to, and suppliers don't know when labs might need something. And that's where CloudCreate,

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:30.480
[Guest]: my startup, was formed. It was to address this data asymmetry and help scientists get

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:35.120
[Guest]: their products on time. It's been about two years now, still addressing the problem, but

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:40.280
[Guest]: we now have a much better understanding of the nodal points that need to be changed.

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:45.600
[Guest]: So hopefully, that will sort some things out. The policy bit is because, again, I found

00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:52.280
[Guest]: scientists in India not engaging so much in policymaking. And I felt as a result, our

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:58.040
[Guest]: policymaking is not very attuned to help scientists. Our policymakers are not always using evidence

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:03.880
[Guest]: based policymaking. They don't always seem very keen on talking to scientists and understanding

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:08.440
[Guest]: what issues there might be. And so I thought I could be a bridge between that. And hence,

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:12.080
[Guest]: I started coming to Dakshashila. The point was to understand how I could better engage

00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:17.240
[Guest]: with the government. And then once I actually saw how the government processes were, and

00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:21.720
[Guest]: there were parts of legislation where I could actually provide a scientist insight too,

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:27.280
[Guest]: I wanted to. So that's how I got into policymaking and gene editing. And the fact that gene editing

00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:33.520
[Guest]: is coming up, and we did not have a good enough policy to support it, was how I got engaged

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:37.160
[Guest]: in trying to write up a policy for gene editing itself.

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:42.320
[Amit Varma]: So you know, just assuming that, you know, me and my listeners are kind of laymen, and,

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:46.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, we don't really know the science too much. And I know, it's a very broad question.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But tell me about the state of where genetics is at today. Like, you know, obviously, genetics,

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, brings out explains very clearly and elegantly fundamental truths about what

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:00.640
[Amit Varma]: the universe is, you know, I earlier quoted Adams talking about natural selection and

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:05.560
[Amit Varma]: genes are obviously the vehicle through which natural selection happens, as you know, Richard

00:14:05.560 --> 00:14:09.640
[Amit Varma]: Dawkins wrote his famous book, The Selfish Gene, which popularised that and you know,

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:13.600
[Amit Varma]: when he spoke about the selfish gene, obviously, that was a metaphor. I mean, a gene isn't

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:19.160
[Amit Varma]: actually thinking selfishly. But take me a little bit through the process of how it works,

00:14:19.160 --> 00:14:24.680
[Amit Varma]: like how have we been designed if you can kind of speak about in layman's language?

00:14:24.680 --> 00:14:29.120
[Amit Varma]: How have we been designed? How do our genetics? Yeah, in the sense that how are we what we

00:14:29.120 --> 00:14:35.000
[Amit Varma]: are like, you know, human 30,000 years ago would have been very different. And 500,000

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:40.160
[Amit Varma]: years ago, wherever we came from, I mean, to begin with, we came out of one celled organisms.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And then that one cell organisms basically evolved into everything. And the process is

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:51.040
[Amit Varma]: so beautiful and elegant. And yeah, we did come from soup. And when I you know, catch

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:59.040
[Amit Varma]: a virus, I often go back to soup. But sorry. Take us through some of the elegance of this

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:01.800
[Amit Varma]: process and the role that genes the central role that genes play.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:06.640
[Guest]: Okay, so there's there's a lot that we can unpackage here, right? Let me give you one

00:15:06.640 --> 00:15:11.280
[Guest]: example, which is my favourite example. So we obviously think that humans are different

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:17.280
[Guest]: because our brains work very differently than all other species, right? We are intelligent.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:22.320
[Guest]: So the reason we have brains with that kind of firepower, there are two underlying reasons

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:26.840
[Guest]: and one is nature, one is nurture. Okay, I don't remember timeliness, I'm sorry. But

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:33.080
[Guest]: many, many years ago, there was one mutation in one of our ancestors, which changed the

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:38.060
[Guest]: location of the jaw, because of which the skull moved a bit, and there was more space

00:15:38.060 --> 00:15:43.960
[Guest]: created for the brain. So the brain could actually grow more in our ancestors. And as

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:49.180
[Guest]: a result of that, we actually have more brain space than apes. That was one thing that changed.

00:15:49.180 --> 00:15:53.920
[Guest]: The other was we discovered fire. And because we had fire, we could cook food. And because

00:15:53.920 --> 00:16:00.680
[Guest]: you're eating cooked food, we could now decrease the amount of energy that was devoted to digestion.

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:05.240
[Guest]: And so more energy could be spent on the brain. At the same time, because we are eating cooked

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:11.280
[Guest]: food, the amount of gut surface that we require for digestion was also reduced. So our gut

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:15.800
[Guest]: size reduced, again, the energy consumption of the gut reduced, and all of that energy

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:21.600
[Guest]: was diverted to the brain. And because of those two things, we actually managed to develop

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:27.400
[Guest]: better brain power than the other species. So I've also like read a theory that it's

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:33.080
[Amit Varma]: also because we see homo sapiens started eating non-veg. And you know, the proteins help them

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:37.800
[Amit Varma]: grow bigger brains to fit the craniums. And one theory is we ate the Neanderthals. So

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:41.600
[Guest]: I don't know how. I don't know if we ate them or not. We all have a bit of Neanderthal

00:16:41.600 --> 00:16:47.920
[Guest]: in us. Yeah. Which did not come from eating them. Exactly. Yeah, it is likely. Look, at

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:54.320
[Guest]: that point of time, this is pre-agriculture. So and they were hunter-gatherers. So there

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:58.760
[Guest]: is also this theory that because we came from hunter-gatherers, we were more used to eating

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:05.700
[Guest]: meat proteins than actually carbs. And then when agrarian practices came in, our bodies

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:12.640
[Guest]: are still shifting to eating more wheat and rice. So we see some changes, for example,

00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:16.360
[Guest]: in some of the bones in our body that are still trying to fit together into this whole

00:17:16.360 --> 00:17:21.600
[Guest]: agrarian lifestyle. And so we are not meant to be eating carbs. Yeah, we just both of

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:27.880
[Amit Varma]: us had masala dosa for lunch at MTR. And but of course, we both agree intellectually that

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:32.120
[Guest]: sugar is poison, however hard it is to sort of. Yeah. And we are basically supposed to

00:17:32.120 --> 00:17:37.680
[Guest]: be protein eaters. So that shift has occurred. For our bodies to adjust to that shift is

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:42.240
[Guest]: going to take a long time. They are still adjusting to that idea that we are now eating

00:17:42.240 --> 00:17:47.000
[Guest]: this carb, fat-based diet and obviously not doing as much work as the hunter-gatherers

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:52.800
[Guest]: were doing at all, having this sedentary life. And we are still trying to fix up to that.

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:57.600
[Guest]: My idea is that maybe in a few million years ago, there might only be slim humans around

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:03.200
[Guest]: because obesity increases your chances of death. And maybe we will get naturally selected

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:07.880
[Guest]: to be thin. And if I have a time machine, I would like to go into that era and just

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:11.480
[Guest]: be thin and eat whatever I want to still be thin. That would be nice.

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:18.200
[Amit Varma]: I think that is a common lament that both of us can sort of share. So I'll briefly for

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:22.640
[Amit Varma]: my listeners, I'll sort of give a very simplified understanding of what genes do. Tell me if

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:27.280
[Amit Varma]: I make a beginner's error or something. But essentially, what genes do is genes are sort

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:33.200
[Amit Varma]: of our programming. So all our characteristics are written down in genes and often mutations

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:37.880
[Amit Varma]: happen and different characteristics evolve in different ways. Now, for example, let's

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:44.560
[Amit Varma]: say due to an accidental mutation of my gene, I get, say, a bigger nose. And we're talking

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:48.640
[Amit Varma]: prehistoric times, I get a bigger nose. And it so happens that women find bigger noses

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:54.640
[Amit Varma]: much more attractive. And therefore I reproduce more. And because I reproduce more, that particular

00:18:54.640 --> 00:19:00.240
[Amit Varma]: gene which gives me a bigger nose has a greater chance of proliferating through the population.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:05.080
[Amit Varma]: So there are more kids with bigger noses who are having more kids while those with smaller

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:11.540
[Amit Varma]: noses are not mating as much. And therefore, eventually, the gene for small noses goes

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:15.400
[Amit Varma]: out of the gene pool. And this is, of course, extremely simplified because it's not as if

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:20.200
[Amit Varma]: one gene creates one characteristic. It's very complex. It's whatever, but women don't

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:26.040
[Amit Varma]: pick noses as a criteria for reproducing. Yeah, this was just an example. Yeah, I have

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:29.440
[Guest]: no idea what women pick as a criteria. But I mean, this is the correct thing, right?

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:36.080
[Guest]: That your nature basically chooses what, which specimen is best suited to survive in it.

00:19:36.080 --> 00:19:40.440
[Guest]: In fact, to reproduce. Yeah, yeah, to reproduce. So, and most likely

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:45.840
[Guest]: driver is food. It's food resources. So if you're a giraffe and you have a longer neck

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:51.240
[Guest]: and you can eat leaves which are at the taller part of the plant than other animals of average

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:55.960
[Guest]: size and obviously have more food and so you will get, you'll reproduce more. So we used

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:59.960
[Guest]: to at some point of time also have giraffes with shorter necks, but those died out in

00:19:59.960 --> 00:20:03.800
[Amit Varma]: competition and the longer neck ones. Because one, the longer necks one would have

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:08.440
[Amit Varma]: survived and thus greater chances of having a kid. And two, at the level of the female

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:14.340
[Amit Varma]: giraffes, the ones who would have been attracted towards the longer neck giraffes would also

00:20:14.340 --> 00:20:19.200
[Amit Varma]: have mated more with them and therefore their kids were not just the longer necks would

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:25.160
[Amit Varma]: have passed on to the kids, but also the attraction for longer necks because pretty much all our

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:31.400
[Amit Varma]: tendencies and everything is sort of, in a sense, comes from our genes. Like, you know,

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:36.640
[Amit Varma]: just talking about nature and nurture. Steven Pinker once gave a lovely illustration of

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:40.000
[Amit Varma]: this, which I think expresses it very well, because obviously it's a false binary and

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:45.520
[Amit Varma]: there's both nature and nurture in everything we do. And he said, nature gives us knobs,

00:20:45.520 --> 00:20:49.960
[Amit Varma]: nurture turns them. So you could have a very big knob for something, like you could be

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:54.400
[Amit Varma]: someone who has a very bad temper and that's in your genes. But if you have the kind of

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:58.120
[Amit Varma]: upbringing where you're not supposed to get angry, then maybe that knob is not turned

00:20:58.120 --> 00:21:04.300
[Guest]: so much. That is actually true. So there are these genes, if they're mutated, you can be

00:21:04.300 --> 00:21:11.320
[Guest]: extremely aggressive by temperament, but obviously not all aggressive people are criminals. So

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:15.520
[Guest]: there was a study done to try and figure out whether you could have a genetic basis for

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:19.880
[Guest]: criminality and you can have a genetic basis for determining if someone might be more or

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:25.840
[Guest]: less aggressive. But the criminality comes then as an add-on of nurture and the environment

00:21:25.840 --> 00:21:30.080
[Amit Varma]: that they've been in and what they've learned. And this also reminds me of a study, and I've

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:34.400
[Amit Varma]: written a column on this as well, on how sociopaths, and now sociopath is a particular biological

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:37.320
[Amit Varma]: term, there's a part, I think the amygdala, there's a part of the brain which is slightly

00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:41.480
[Amit Varma]: damaged, so they don't feel empathy. It's a biological characteristic that they don't

00:21:41.480 --> 00:21:47.160
[Amit Varma]: feel empathy. And sociopaths are over-represented, like they're 5% of the population overall,

00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:53.680
[Amit Varma]: something like that, but they're over-represented in criminals, bankers and politicians, as

00:21:53.680 --> 00:21:59.200
[Amit Varma]: far as I recall, which indicates that these skills are, you know, what the genes are.

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.880
[Guest]: The lack of empathy might be very useful in getting ahead of...

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:05.840
[Guest]: In banking sales, yes, I think so.

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:11.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you know, the thing there is that before we pass judgment, like, are all sociopaths

00:22:11.560 --> 00:22:16.080
[Amit Varma]: bad people? No, they are not, because you're born the way you're born. And I always, you

00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:20.360
[Amit Varma]: know, try to judge people by their behaviour. If you are born the way you are, there is

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:26.240
[Amit Varma]: nothing you can do about that. And therefore, all of us have baser instincts. And, you know,

00:22:26.240 --> 00:22:30.520
[Amit Varma]: we should not start loathing ourselves because we have those baser instincts, whatever they

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:35.520
[Amit Varma]: might be towards violence or tribalism or whatever. But we should, once we are aware

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:40.480
[Amit Varma]: of, once we have a certain moral view of the world, just as long as we behave properly,

00:22:40.480 --> 00:22:43.880
[Amit Varma]: that's what matters. People should be judged by their behaviour. I'm getting extremely

00:22:43.880 --> 00:22:49.240
[Amit Varma]: ahead of myself and ourselves here. Tell me a bit more about the development of the science

00:22:49.240 --> 00:22:51.760
[Amit Varma]: and how we kind of reach this modern age.

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:56.880
[Guest]: Let me go back to something that you said about how the awe of the whole idea of genetics

00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:01.880
[Guest]: is better than the awe of divinity. And when scientists actually first figured out, so

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:07.520
[Guest]: when Charles Darwin, for example, looked at evolution and natural selection, when James

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:13.240
[Guest]: Watson looked at the structure of the DNA, both the scientists, the first thing that

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:17.480
[Guest]: came into their head was that they were going to be challenging some of the most accepted

00:23:17.480 --> 00:23:22.360
[Guest]: religious knowledge back then, because they were basically saying that there is a natural

00:23:22.360 --> 00:23:27.720
[Guest]: cause to the way we are, and this is not divine intervention. And both have gone through this

00:23:27.720 --> 00:23:33.440
[Guest]: in their notes about the idea that whether the challenge was successful. Charles Darwin

00:23:33.440 --> 00:23:40.160
[Guest]: obviously got a lot of hate email, spam email, whatever, from the church for putting forth

00:23:40.160 --> 00:23:44.680
[Guest]: the principles of natural selection. But then science relies on facts, not on opinions.

00:23:44.680 --> 00:23:49.960
[Guest]: So they could clearly see that there was a way that nature was choosing to act in a way.

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:54.840
[Guest]: So right from Charles Darwin, we had then we had Gregor Mendel, who was a monk and most

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:59.840
[Guest]: of his scientific experiments were done in his parish. So, which was...

00:23:59.840 --> 00:24:04.760
[Amit Varma]: And his seminal paper was ignored for like 50 years because it came out in some obscure

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:05.760
[Guest]: things.

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:09.800
[Guest]: Yeah, that's an occupational hazard of being in science. But they did do meticulous work.

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:14.200
[Guest]: Gregor Mendel obviously spent years working on peas. And what he did was basically show

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:21.120
[Guest]: that there was a factor in peas that was controlling the way peas looked. So, the way this happens

00:24:21.120 --> 00:24:26.200
[Guest]: is that genes forms proteins, and proteins basically govern the characteristics of your

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:32.360
[Guest]: body. So, physical, mental, to some extent behavioural, proteins play a role in literally

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:37.960
[Guest]: most things that go on in your body. My favourite example is the colour of your skin, because

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:43.760
[Guest]: not only is it dependent on proteins, but also on the way sun reacts and the amount

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:48.920
[Guest]: of time you spend in the sun. And the colour of the skin also provides a nice ethical challenge

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:49.920
[Guest]: for us to talk about.

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:55.600
[Guest]: So, the way it works is that the DNA in the skin cells will form some proteins that will

00:24:55.600 --> 00:25:00.520
[Guest]: control the colour of the skin. Similar to that, the colour of your eyes, the strength

00:25:00.520 --> 00:25:06.080
[Guest]: of your heart muscle, the length of your gut, everything gets controlled by proteins. So,

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:10.920
[Guest]: what Mendel was observing was the proteins in action. So, he was looking either at the

00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:14.280
[Guest]: way the peas were, whether they were smooth, whether they were wrinkled, the colour of

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:19.880
[Guest]: the flowers, etc, etc. And what he found was that the characteristics could be passed from

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:24.920
[Guest]: generation to generation. And so, he said that there must be some factor present inside

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:30.160
[Guest]: the pea plant, which is crossing across generations. And this was the first indication that maybe

00:25:30.160 --> 00:25:33.000
[Guest]: God was not playing a hand at creating the pea plant.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:37.920
[Guest]: After that, his paper, as you said, was buried for a long time, till people again started

00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:42.560
[Guest]: looking at the DNA molecule. And this is where it is all started, because the DNA is so small,

00:25:42.560 --> 00:25:47.800
[Guest]: we knew that it was made up of only four alphabets, A, T, G, and C. It just did not seem likely

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:52.840
[Guest]: that this would be that elusive code that was governing everything in life. It just

00:25:52.840 --> 00:25:57.840
[Guest]: seemed unrealistic. But then, in the early 20th century, a lot of experiments were done

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:04.200
[Guest]: to show that whatever factor it was residing in the nucleus, then people did laborious

00:26:04.200 --> 00:26:09.440
[Guest]: experiments, they first killed off all proteins, all RNA, everything else in the cell, and

00:26:09.440 --> 00:26:15.320
[Guest]: they showed that it was a DNA that can pass on from bacteria to bacteria, and cause characteristics

00:26:15.320 --> 00:26:23.360
[Guest]: to also manifest once passed on. So, it took us about 50 years, and a lot of debate to

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:28.640
[Guest]: figure out that the DNA was actually what was causing characteristics to be formed.

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:34.200
[Guest]: And in the middle of all of that, we had this guy called Lysenko in Russia, who came and

00:26:34.200 --> 00:26:40.400
[Guest]: said that genetics is bullshit. There is nothing like genes, there is no genetics, we can give

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:44.400
[Guest]: shock therapy to everything and make it behave the way we want it to. So, he was doing his

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:49.640
[Guest]: experiments on plants. But then he came and said that, okay, why don't we also do it on

00:26:49.640 --> 00:26:54.960
[Guest]: humans? Stalin was by then the premier of Russia, and Stalin really bought into this

00:26:54.960 --> 00:27:00.760
[Guest]: theory. So, he was like, okay, let us do this. And a lot of geneticists were either killed

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:05.160
[Guest]: in Russia or they fled Russia. A lot of the prisoners of war were then taken and given

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:09.880
[Guest]: shock therapy to believe in Russian propaganda. And obviously, as I mentioned, none of that

00:27:09.880 --> 00:27:16.360
[Guest]: went anywhere. But we did have that phase. Germany, on the other hand, Germany, UK, US,

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:20.640
[Guest]: had their own dalliance with genetics. Now I'm going into eugenics, because once they

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:26.080
[Guest]: figured out that there was something like the DNA, which could actually encode for characteristics,

00:27:26.080 --> 00:27:29.280
[Guest]: they thought, well, then there must be pure DNA as well, because some characteristics

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:34.680
[Guest]: are better than the others. And this, I think, is the ultimate flaw of genetics. And the

00:27:34.680 --> 00:27:40.400
[Guest]: ultimate flaw of the way we look at society today is that we choose what are the good

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.760
[Guest]: and bad characteristics. We think we have a moral say on whether longer, bigger noses

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:51.480
[Guest]: are prettier than smaller noses, and whether a very small nose is a freaky one. These are

00:27:51.480 --> 00:27:58.480
[Guest]: societal ideas. In nature, everything is okay. Everything is acceptable. So obviously, we

00:27:58.480 --> 00:28:04.160
[Guest]: had the entire phase of eugenics, started in the US actually, but then championed by

00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:07.760
[Guest]: Germany. And this was again, before we had figured out the structure of the DNA, this

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:12.080
[Guest]: was when we realized that the DNA exists and that the DNA can actually pass characteristics

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:18.200
[Guest]: on. Then in 1953, came the hallmark discovery of the structure of the DNA based on the work

00:28:18.200 --> 00:28:23.880
[Guest]: of James Watson, Francis Creek, Morris Wilkins, and obviously, Rosalind Franklin, who gets

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:29.040
[Guest]: zero to minimal credit for it. To be fair, she was also not the most cooperative person

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:33.720
[Guest]: to work on the project with, but it was her X-rays that eventually led to the discovery

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:40.760
[Guest]: of the structure of the DNA. That changed a lot of perceptions in the game of molecular

00:28:40.760 --> 00:28:45.280
[Guest]: biology and opened up the field of genetics. Because once we knew the structure, people

00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:50.760
[Guest]: could actually go about in trying to then start reading the structure, editing the structure,

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:54.560
[Guest]: amplifying the structure. And so from the 1950s, we have made remarkable discoveries.

00:28:54.560 --> 00:28:58.920
[Guest]: One of our chief problems starting out was that there is very less DNA if you think about

00:28:58.920 --> 00:29:03.680
[Guest]: it in a cell. So the first thing to do if we wanted to analyze the DNA was to amplify

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:09.400
[Guest]: it. And that's where the most remarkable things came in the terms of polymerase chain reaction,

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:13.320
[Guest]: which is so commonly used now. Any lab you go to will have a PCR machine. We learned

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:17.400
[Guest]: to sequence the DNA so we were able to read it. A lot of these experiments were initially

00:29:17.400 --> 00:29:22.400
[Guest]: done in like flies, so the fruit fly that we see. That's a very commonly used model

00:29:22.400 --> 00:29:28.200
[Guest]: system in worms, which are so tiny that you need a microscope to see them. But a lot of,

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:31.760
[Guest]: say the proteins in the field I work in, of cell death, of how cells die, were actually

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:36.920
[Guest]: discovered in the worm. And then we found out the human equivalents of those. And all

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:42.080
[Guest]: of these pathways are remarkably well conserved. So you might have an additional protein here

00:29:42.080 --> 00:29:48.160
[Guest]: or a slightly little detour of pathway there. But most of those things are pretty same from

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:52.080
[Guest]: worms to flies to mice to humans, which is why you see a lot of the experiments being

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:57.000
[Guest]: done in mice as well. So a lot of the initial work got done in them because the human is

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:04.560
[Guest]: a complex organism to get the DNA out of. So bacteria only have genes in their DNA.

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:10.000
[Guest]: Humans have something known as introns, which are massive stretches of DNA, which code for

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.440
[Guest]: nothing or at least we don't understand what they code for. So we have a lot of junk DNA

00:30:14.440 --> 00:30:20.040
[Guest]: as well. So it took us a little bit of time to go from the bacteria to actually sequence

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:25.240
[Guest]: the entire human genome. The first human genome was obviously made in 2003 and we spent a

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:30.320
[Guest]: few billion dollars on trying to sequence it. But once we understood the sequence of

00:30:30.320 --> 00:30:35.520
[Guest]: the gene, we could start understanding what proteins it makes and therefore what pathways

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:40.720
[Guest]: it governs, what characteristics it governs. And at the same time, we started to also learn

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:45.760
[Guest]: how to edit the genes, but not in humans, in bacteria, because it's a pretty simple

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:50.320
[Guest]: genome and it's usually a single cell. So it's easy for us to also send in material

00:30:50.320 --> 00:30:54.560
[Guest]: and in and out of the cell. So we've been doing this whole gene editing, but in bacteria

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:58.720
[Guest]: for a very, very long time. We can also do it in single cells, which are derived from

00:30:58.720 --> 00:31:05.040
[Guest]: human beings. But the idea that we could rewrite the code on our own in a very precise manner

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:09.880
[Guest]: only came with CRISPR technology. CRISPR, of course, is a dating app for genes.

00:31:09.880 --> 00:31:13.680
[Amit Varma]: Of course it is. So CRISPR was discovered in 1987. So tell

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:19.200
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit more about that. What does CRISPR do and, you know, why is it so revolutionary?

00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:24.800
[Guest]: As with most things we do, we have also adopted CRISPR from bacteria. So we have an immune

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:31.120
[Guest]: system, we have antibodies, we have B cells, T cells, which basically kill any foreign

00:31:31.120 --> 00:31:35.760
[Guest]: particle that enters into our body. Bacteria are single cells, so they don't really have

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:40.320
[Guest]: the luxury of having this entire complement of immune cells. And the most common adversary

00:31:40.320 --> 00:31:46.000
[Guest]: for a bacteria is a virus. So when people were doing these studies, looking at how bacteria

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:51.200
[Guest]: fend off viruses, they found that there were repeats in the bacterial genome, which were

00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:57.120
[Guest]: actually repeats of DNA from viruses. So they thought, and it was like an entire library

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:01.640
[Guest]: of different viral sequences that kept on repeating. So what scientists thought was

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:07.520
[Guest]: that maybe these are viruses that this bacteria has already seen. And that is where the concept

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:11.880
[Guest]: of this being an immune system response came in. So what the bacteria actually does is

00:32:11.880 --> 00:32:17.400
[Guest]: that when a virus comes in and it chops up the DNA, it takes a bit of the DNA, of the

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:22.680
[Guest]: viral DNA, puts it into its own genome, and keeps it on file. So that the next time this

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:27.440
[Guest]: virus comes in again, they can match it and chop it off immediately. So they can match

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:32.800
[Guest]: the DNA to the existing one inside the bacterial genome, go and chop off the viral genome.

00:32:32.800 --> 00:32:37.400
[Guest]: And then they build a library that way of every new virus. And this entire idea that

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:43.640
[Guest]: you can read a genome, and then you can go look for a similar genome, and cut it is the

00:32:43.640 --> 00:32:49.440
[Guest]: underlining part of CRISPR. So what we did is that we use those genes that develops this

00:32:49.440 --> 00:32:55.800
[Guest]: machinery and put it in humans. We also modulated a bit. So now you can specify this is the

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:59.680
[Guest]: bit of the genome I want to cut, so that the machinery will go and cut there. But then

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:04.040
[Guest]: you can also specify what genome you want to put in its place. And that is what the

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:08.480
[Guest]: machinery does. It is basically like a copy and paste function, where you cut and paste

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:12.280
[Guest]: function, where you specify where you want to cut and what you want to paste.

00:33:12.280 --> 00:33:16.560
[Amit Varma]: Let me try to sort of process the whole sort of historical arc that you've described. There's

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:21.480
[Amit Varma]: a theory that the pace of change doesn't, you know, accelerates over time. So for example,

00:33:21.480 --> 00:33:25.600
[Amit Varma]: we took 1000s of years to get from the agricultural age to the industrial age, and then a couple

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:30.240
[Amit Varma]: of 100 years from there to get to the information age. And now it's getting faster and faster.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, within the microcosm of what has been happening in this field, it seems

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:39.280
[Amit Varma]: to me a similar thing. I mean, you know, just to think of Mendel, for example, who on his

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:44.040
[Amit Varma]: own without a, you know, a body of a field of work to help him has discovered something

00:33:44.040 --> 00:33:48.800
[Amit Varma]: has discovered that there is heritability, but not figured out that genes are a mechanism

00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:53.120
[Amit Varma]: for it. Because obviously, he can't it must seem to him that there is a mysterious force

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:58.520
[Amit Varma]: which is doing that, which reminds me of the old saying that a sufficiently advanced technology

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:03.960
[Amit Varma]: is like magic, which is, I'm sure how it would have seemed to Mendel. And and then eventually

00:34:03.960 --> 00:34:08.640
[Amit Varma]: 50 years pass, his paper is discovered this work happening on genes. And then of course,

00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:13.360
[Amit Varma]: the DNA is, you know, after World War Two, the DNA is finally decoded, and we understand

00:34:13.360 --> 00:34:18.840
[Amit Varma]: the structure and it's so beautiful and elegant. And gradually people start figuring that out,

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:23.720
[Amit Varma]: then it seems to me that there are like, two things which happen very fast in sequence.

00:34:23.720 --> 00:34:29.400
[Amit Varma]: One is that people begin to figure out what genes cause, you know, what characteristics

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.320
[Amit Varma]: and what are the functions and the purposes of genes and the human genome project happens,

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:39.800
[Amit Varma]: which costs I think, $2.7 or $3.7 billion. And today, you can sequence it for $100, which

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:45.040
[Amit Varma]: shows our commonplace it's become. And after that, with CRISPR, and even, you know, technologies

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:48.720
[Amit Varma]: before it, but especially CRISPR onwards, people figure out not only what genes do,

00:34:48.720 --> 00:34:54.440
[Amit Varma]: but how you can actually edit genes and change genes. And therefore, and what are the implications

00:34:54.440 --> 00:34:58.320
[Amit Varma]: of that, like when we're talking about gene editing, I'm guessing there are two aspects

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:05.680
[Amit Varma]: to it. One aspect is that you do gene editing in an individual. For example, if I have some

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:11.160
[Amit Varma]: kind of deformity, which is caused by a gene, can you edit my genome and make me better

00:35:11.160 --> 00:35:15.960
[Amit Varma]: or prevent something happening in future, which I'm inclined towards. And the second,

00:35:15.960 --> 00:35:19.600
[Amit Varma]: I guess would be just changing the entire line, you know, editing my genes in such a

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:24.000
[Amit Varma]: way that I'm passing on the edited version to any kids that I might have, and therefore

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:28.640
[Guest]: it passes on. Are these broadly the sort of... Yeah, so there are certain nomenclature issues

00:35:28.640 --> 00:35:33.360
[Guest]: that are currently going around in gene editing. One set calls them somatic versus germline

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:38.040
[Guest]: gene editing. Somatic being in any cell of your body that will not contribute into your

00:35:38.040 --> 00:35:44.160
[Guest]: child's development. And therefore, any edit done in that cell will remain to you. Versus

00:35:44.160 --> 00:35:48.680
[Guest]: germline editing, germlines are those cells, which are those germ cells will basically

00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:54.080
[Guest]: contribute to the development of your child. So, any change we make in those will also

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:58.120
[Guest]: go down to your child and any subsequent children that that child has, right. So, they will

00:35:58.120 --> 00:36:04.240
[Guest]: impact entire future generation that comes out of you. The way we do somatic gene editing

00:36:04.240 --> 00:36:09.040
[Guest]: in itself, there are two ways. One is either you take out cells from your body, you do

00:36:09.040 --> 00:36:13.560
[Guest]: the gene editing in a petri dish and you put the cells back in. Or you put in a virus into

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:19.440
[Guest]: a person that takes the machinery for gene editing and transfers it into the cells in

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:24.840
[Guest]: the body and does gene editing. If we do this in vivo, in vivo being inside the body kind

00:36:24.840 --> 00:36:31.440
[Guest]: of way, we do not have a guarantee that the germ cells in your body will not be edited,

00:36:31.440 --> 00:36:37.680
[Guest]: ok. We can hypothetically say that they should not, but we do not actually have any control.

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:42.240
[Amit Varma]: So, if it was somatic thing in vivo only meant for me, it could also go into the germline?

00:36:42.240 --> 00:36:46.640
[Guest]: Could go into your germline, right. We actually have very little proof. We do not, we need

00:36:46.640 --> 00:36:51.840
[Guest]: to do more extensive experiments for that. So, the way the WHO says we should call them

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:57.600
[Guest]: is heritable versus unheritable gene editing. And so, somatic gene editing could also fall

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:02.280
[Guest]: into the heritable part. We just do not know yet. We need to do more exhaustive experimentation

00:37:02.280 --> 00:37:08.600
[Guest]: to figure that one out. The ethical considerations of heritable versus non-heritable are extremely

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:12.920
[Guest]: diverse. People are usually ok if you want to do something to change your body, you want

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:17.880
[Guest]: to have a tattoo, you want to drink sugar-laced coffee, it is up to you. But if that is going

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:23.000
[Guest]: to also impact your child and their child, then obviously people think that you are tampering

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:28.440
[Guest]: with something that is likely beyond you. So, we are still to, that is a very grey zone

00:37:28.440 --> 00:37:31.840
[Guest]: and I am sure we will talk about it in further detail. But yes, at this point of time for

00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:36.200
[Guest]: humans there are these two ways, heritable and non-heritable. Also, we have been trying

00:37:36.200 --> 00:37:41.280
[Guest]: to do gene editing in plants, but that we have been doing for ages by one means or the

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:46.640
[Guest]: other. We are trying to do gene editing in mosquitoes, in flies, and also some really

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:52.080
[Guest]: weird applications where people are trying to say take the Indian elephant, genetically

00:37:52.080 --> 00:37:58.280
[Guest]: modify it so that it can survive cold weathers and put it in Siberia so that the Indian elephant

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:02.720
[Guest]: does not die out. So, the Indian elephant does not die out, they want to send it to

00:38:02.720 --> 00:38:08.760
[Guest]: Siberia. Or they are trying to figure out how, why honeybees are dying and how we can

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:12.960
[Guest]: use gene editing to actually prevent honeybees from dying. So, there is this whole concept

00:38:12.960 --> 00:38:18.040
[Guest]: of the clean honeybee. So, apparently there are some honeybees which keep their hives

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:22.640
[Guest]: clean, some which are like me and do not. So, the clean honeybees live longer and so

00:38:22.640 --> 00:38:25.440
[Guest]: they are trying to figure out what genetic differences there are between the clean and

00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:29.840
[Guest]: the unclean honeybees and trying to create more clean honeybees.

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:33.720
[Amit Varma]: And one thing that I think is worth pointing out is that when we talk about gene editing,

00:38:33.720 --> 00:38:38.200
[Amit Varma]: we are of course talking about gene editing now with all these tools and, you know, designing

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:42.680
[Amit Varma]: these changes, so to say. But we are actually products of gene editing that right from the

00:38:42.680 --> 00:38:46.960
[Amit Varma]: time there was that first one celled organism, there has been continuous gene editing, which

00:38:46.960 --> 00:38:52.640
[Amit Varma]: has come down to us most of it completely random with natural selection having its way.

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:58.160
[Amit Varma]: And you know, gene editing has sort of happened by random and through nature and all that.

00:38:58.160 --> 00:39:03.240
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there's been a lot of sort of conscious gene editing that has happened

00:39:03.240 --> 00:39:08.040
[Amit Varma]: that has resulted, for example, like in dogs, like 15,000 years ago in Central Asia, you

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:12.480
[Amit Varma]: basically you know, these experiments started where there were some wolves which were friendlier

00:39:12.480 --> 00:39:18.120
[Amit Varma]: than others. And then they were sort of, you know, bred by humans. And eventually you have

00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:24.280
[Amit Varma]: domestic dogs. And similarly, mules are basically an example of, you know, you mate a donkey

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:28.760
[Amit Varma]: with a horse and you get mules. And that's, in a sense, gene editing that you're kind

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:32.640
[Amit Varma]: of carrying out. So, you know, a lot of the mysticism that is there around these terms

00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:36.760
[Amit Varma]: as if it's some horrible dystopian science fiction thing happening, gene editing and

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:40.920
[Amit Varma]: all of that. The only thing that has changed is that we understand it better and we are

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:44.240
[Amit Varma]: trying to control it better. And actually, it's like it's been there forever.

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:48.320
[Guest]: Yeah, it has been there forever, except that the driver has changed. The driver in most

00:39:48.320 --> 00:39:54.960
[Guest]: cases was nature. And then, obviously, all your surrounding ecosystem got to play a role

00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:59.440
[Guest]: in your development. So, the other species also got to have some say in how, what your

00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:04.400
[Guest]: population was, what kind of skills you developed, whether you were a burrower or whether you

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:09.600
[Guest]: were going to stay up on a tree, your entire ecosystem fed into that. We have moved from

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:15.480
[Guest]: that to a system where humans can be as selfish as they want to be and pick on things that

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:21.240
[Guest]: we think are necessary for our existence and only help those survive, which is a little

00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:25.040
[Guest]: scary, because I'm not sure whether we have a complete understanding of what we need to

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:30.920
[Guest]: survive. But apart from the change in the driver, gene editing has been a part of nature

00:40:30.920 --> 00:40:36.760
[Guest]: ever since, before even we came along. I mean, that's how we came along, was through modification

00:40:36.760 --> 00:40:42.360
[Guest]: of genes. There is a distrust in the idea, like you said. When I was in the UK, this

00:40:42.360 --> 00:40:50.080
[Guest]: was about six or seven years ago. And Europe is extremely well known for its risk awareness

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:55.880
[Guest]: and they really, really take it seriously. And one of the, this was when GMOs were making

00:40:55.880 --> 00:41:00.960
[Guest]: a mark on the scene. One of the headlines in the newspaper I used to get at home said,

00:41:00.960 --> 00:41:07.800
[Guest]: oh, but GMO tomatoes have DNA in them. And I was like, but all tomatoes have DNA in them.

00:41:07.800 --> 00:41:14.360
[Guest]: There is nothing unique about GMOs and I mean, the DNA is slightly modified, that's it. But

00:41:14.360 --> 00:41:20.520
[Guest]: so is every other tomato's DNA. Every time you regenerate, you gather a mutation. That's

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:25.920
[Guest]: the way life works. So there's nothing, yeah, there's nothing fancy about gene editing itself.

00:41:25.920 --> 00:41:30.400
[Guest]: The only scary part is that now we are the ones who can do it. And so we have to do it

00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:31.400
[Guest]: intelligently enough.

00:41:31.400 --> 00:41:35.640
[Amit Varma]: Then one of the things, you know, one of the constant stories of humanity, for example,

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:41.160
[Amit Varma]: one of the constant battles within our species is a battle against our own nature. For example,

00:41:41.160 --> 00:41:44.840
[Amit Varma]: in some ways we are wired to behave in certain ways. We are wired to crave children, but

00:41:44.840 --> 00:41:49.680
[Amit Varma]: people like me fight that by deciding not to have kids or we are wired to be tribalistic.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:55.520
[Amit Varma]: But many of us are, you know, we have a liberal global outlook and don't think in those terms,

00:41:55.520 --> 00:42:00.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, we are wired to want sex more than, you know, some of us actually aim for. And

00:42:00.760 --> 00:42:07.640
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me that a lot of human history is sort of mitigating the programming, mitigating

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:11.600
[Amit Varma]: the way we have been programmed, which is basically happenstance. But because we have

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:16.280
[Amit Varma]: also been programmed to think rationally and build a system of values, we then use those

00:42:16.280 --> 00:42:20.940
[Amit Varma]: values to fight our own programming. And it seems to me that while we have been doing

00:42:20.940 --> 00:42:26.320
[Amit Varma]: that at the level of culture, at the level of nurture, you know, what gene editing and

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:31.960
[Amit Varma]: the new science also does is it allows us to do that at the level of nature with far

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:37.040
[Amit Varma]: more precision than we could have, you know, like we have all striven to improve ourselves

00:42:37.040 --> 00:42:40.680
[Amit Varma]: physically, you know, people will exercise, they will work out, they will go to the gym,

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:45.160
[Amit Varma]: they will run, they will build different capacities for themselves in different ways. If they

00:42:45.160 --> 00:42:49.440
[Amit Varma]: want to stay awake longer, they'll have coffee, they'll use extremely blunt tools. And now

00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:55.560
[Amit Varma]: all that is happening is that our tools are getting finer and finer. And in many ways,

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:57.560
[Guest]: it's almost magical and remarkable.

00:42:57.560 --> 00:43:02.680
[Guest]: It is magical. It's also it is scary, because I think first, we do need to check in where

00:43:02.680 --> 00:43:08.440
[Guest]: a lot of our values and morals come from. The classic case is about sex preferential

00:43:08.440 --> 00:43:13.560
[Guest]: rights, sexual preferences, right? We have been, at least I have been brought up to believe

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:20.360
[Guest]: that being gay or lesbian is not right. It is, I mean, it is not acceptable, it is not

00:43:20.360 --> 00:43:28.360
[Guest]: socially correct, right. And a lot of the science that goes beyond understanding sexual

00:43:28.360 --> 00:43:32.400
[Guest]: preferences was also for some time tinged with this idea that we are looking for an

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:39.640
[Guest]: abnormality, right, we are looking for the gay gene. And we figured out that, look, genetics

00:43:39.640 --> 00:43:46.120
[Guest]: has a role to play in choosing sexual preferences, then nurture also might have a role to play.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:51.800
[Guest]: But in nature, this is all acceptable. We have taken this social construct of, you have

00:43:51.800 --> 00:43:55.280
[Guest]: to be a boy and you have to be a girl. And if you're a boy, you have to like a girl.

00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:59.360
[Guest]: And if you're a girl, you have to like a boy and try to impose that on biology. And that

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:03.880
[Guest]: doesn't work, right? We have not, we have taken the social constructs that we have been

00:44:03.880 --> 00:44:08.360
[Guest]: brought up with, but we have not been able to embrace our own biology. And there are

00:44:08.360 --> 00:44:12.640
[Guest]: those grey areas. And then you say, okay, we can actually genetically edit someone not

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:18.000
[Guest]: to be gay anymore. That is scary. I mean, you don't, you cannot go into those levels,

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:22.200
[Guest]: right? If you want to say that, okay, we'll do gene edit and try to figure out if someone

00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:28.280
[Guest]: has got a, and this is a very weird word, disease, because then you and I get to choose

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:33.560
[Guest]: what a disease is. And I can say being gay is a disease, right? But that those are those

00:44:33.560 --> 00:44:39.240
[Guest]: areas of science and policy that, that really intrigue me, because finally, science has

00:44:39.240 --> 00:44:46.560
[Guest]: to interplay with society in some some format. But we seem to be for millennia now, just

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:49.200
[Amit Varma]: focused on our society and not enough on our science.

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:53.160
[Amit Varma]: The point you're making is really interesting, because, you know, in a sense, it feeds into

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:57.640
[Amit Varma]: my point and elaborates upon that, you know, it's true that we have been wired in certain

00:44:57.640 --> 00:45:02.720
[Amit Varma]: ways, many of them undesirable. And because of the culture that we build through our rational

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:07.760
[Amit Varma]: thought, we try to fight that wiring. But at the same time, it is true that those ugly

00:45:07.760 --> 00:45:12.720
[Amit Varma]: instincts remain within us. And now that we have the power to shape our nature, before

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:17.160
[Amit Varma]: our culture has completely mitigated all the dark sides of our nature, so to say, and even

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:20.920
[Amit Varma]: that, of course, is subjective, what is dark and what is not, you know, the danger is that

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:26.560
[Amit Varma]: we could actually undo some of the good work and, you know, enhance some of the hard wiring

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:30.480
[Amit Varma]: that we might otherwise disapprove of at a cultural level, for example, the preference

00:45:30.480 --> 00:45:36.580
[Amit Varma]: for male children, or the preference for fair skin, for example, you know, and that opens

