[Amit Varma]: on a lot of things. And Sandel says, quote, to believe that our talents and powers are

00:47:52.600 --> 00:47:58.280
[Amit Varma]: wholly our own doing is to misunderstand our place in creation, to confuse our role with

00:47:58.280 --> 00:48:03.960
[Amit Varma]: God's. Stop quote. And here, besides the invocation of God, who of course doesn't exist, it also

00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:10.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of seems to deny our autonomy and agency. And I'm far more inclined to agree with the

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:17.080
[Amit Varma]: Oxford bioethicist Julian Savulescu, who in the context of in the context of parents gene

00:48:17.080 --> 00:48:21.480
[Amit Varma]: editing for the children to give the children a better life, argued that parents have, quote,

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:27.240
[Amit Varma]: a moral obligation to create children with the best chance of the best life. Stop quote.

00:48:27.240 --> 00:48:32.880
[Amit Varma]: And here, what this sort of school of thinking argues for is to say that, look, this is not

00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:38.240
[Amit Varma]: some random mystical thing which we use, we do a lot of things to make our lives better

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:42.720
[Amit Varma]: to make our health better, and so on and so forth for our children. Now, if we have a

00:48:42.720 --> 00:48:48.040
[Amit Varma]: tool by which we can help our children and fellow human beings and ourselves, why should

00:48:48.040 --> 00:48:54.200
[Amit Varma]: we be coercively stopped from using that tool or getting access to that tool? And you know,

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:59.360
[Amit Varma]: again, this whole sort of romanticization of you know, what is natural and what is not

00:48:59.360 --> 00:49:03.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, first of all, gene editing is natural, except it's being done by nature. And Darwin

00:49:03.580 --> 00:49:10.400
[Amit Varma]: famously described nature as, quote, clumsy, wasteful, blundering, low and horribly cruel.

00:49:10.400 --> 00:49:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And if that sounds like some people, you know, it's not it's nature, people are

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:19.360
[Amit Varma]: nice or responding to incentives. So, you know, and I'm also a very powerful argument

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:23.480
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, really strikes a chord with me is Nick Bostrom's argument, where he talks

00:49:23.480 --> 00:49:29.440
[Amit Varma]: about the reversal argument that, for example, if you are going to stop me from editing my

00:49:29.440 --> 00:49:35.680
[Amit Varma]: kids genes to make him say smarter, then what would you what would you feel if I edited

00:49:35.680 --> 00:49:41.120
[Amit Varma]: my kids genes to make him stupider? Because by stopping me, that is effectively what you're

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:47.120
[Amit Varma]: doing. It is the latter, you know, from a consequential point of view. So, and I get

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:53.520
[Amit Varma]: that there are sort of nuances here in terms of most people would say that what I do with

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:58.720
[Amit Varma]: my own body is my business, as you pointed out earlier, whether I get a tattoo or a funky

00:49:58.720 --> 00:50:04.240
[Amit Varma]: haircut or go on a keto diet. But if I am doing something which has externalities, like

00:50:04.240 --> 00:50:08.880
[Amit Varma]: on future humans, for example, that is a problem. For example, the classic example would be

00:50:08.880 --> 00:50:14.560
[Amit Varma]: that I can inject whatever I want in myself. However, where the anti vaccine people have

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:20.120
[Amit Varma]: it very wrong is that their actions, which go against science, have externalities on

00:50:20.120 --> 00:50:24.600
[Amit Varma]: a whole lot of people, because if 10 people in a neighbourhood don't get themselves vaccinated,

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:29.520
[Amit Varma]: it exposes the rest of the entire neighbourhood to that. So I've tried to kind of sum up the

00:50:29.520 --> 00:50:34.040
[Amit Varma]: different kinds of arguments and you know, what are those sort of how do you see all

00:50:34.040 --> 00:50:39.720
[Guest]: this? Ethics of anything is extremely personal, and extremely contextual. And I might be an

00:50:39.720 --> 00:50:44.640
[Guest]: extremely unethical person to be saying this, because I myself feel that in a certain situation,

00:50:44.640 --> 00:50:49.520
[Guest]: I might take a different ethical stance of it in another situation. And this is the same

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:54.640
[Guest]: person, but you know, if tomorrow, I have to have a child, and if someone comes and

00:50:54.640 --> 00:50:58.840
[Guest]: tells me that your child is going to suffer from a very debilitating disease, but there's

00:50:58.840 --> 00:51:05.320
[Guest]: a scientifically safe gene editing tool that you can use to now correct the child and make

00:51:05.320 --> 00:51:09.160
[Guest]: sure that he's healthy. I don't think I'm going to say no. I really don't. I think it

00:51:09.160 --> 00:51:14.200
[Guest]: would be stupid of me to say no. Yeah, it would be wrong of you to say no. Because it's

00:51:14.200 --> 00:51:18.600
[Guest]: not just for the baby, but for the baby's future generations are also likely to get

00:51:18.600 --> 00:51:24.920
[Guest]: that same kind of defect. And the fact that I would have to undergo, I might need support

00:51:24.920 --> 00:51:29.160
[Guest]: in raising this child, the amount of money that I would have otherwise spent on, you

00:51:29.160 --> 00:51:33.080
[Guest]: know, taking the child on holidays, maybe, or for schooling or whatever other advantages

00:51:33.080 --> 00:51:38.480
[Guest]: that I can give him, it will be spent on trying to fix this kid afterwards. And I really don't

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:43.720
[Guest]: see why I do not get to make that choice. I mean, I think at the end of the day, what

00:51:43.720 --> 00:51:47.840
[Guest]: we can enable is for people to be allowed to make the choice. I'm sure there are other

00:51:47.840 --> 00:51:54.200
[Guest]: people who think that having kids born with a certain kind of disability is their karma,

00:51:54.200 --> 00:52:00.120
[Guest]: just God's way of punishing them for sins. That is their choice. I mean, I would like

00:52:00.120 --> 00:52:05.760
[Guest]: them to also embrace gene editing or any medical therapies that can be used to correct and

00:52:05.760 --> 00:52:10.080
[Guest]: alleviate the child's pain because I mean, to get better karma, do something else. Don't

00:52:10.080 --> 00:52:15.520
[Amit Varma]: put that poor child under stress. Yeah, and I mean, you are dealt the cards you are dealt.

00:52:15.520 --> 00:52:19.640
[Amit Varma]: But if you can change them, or if you can at least make sure your kid gets better cards

00:52:19.640 --> 00:52:25.080
[Amit Varma]: and he or she otherwise would, why not? And at some level, is it also then a question

00:52:25.080 --> 00:52:27.600
[Guest]: of individual liberty versus the so called community good?

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:31.480
[Guest]: Gene editing is so complicated, because there's so many ways you can use it. And I think every

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:36.480
[Guest]: use case has a different framework of what you can scientifically is achievable, what

00:52:36.480 --> 00:52:42.320
[Guest]: is ethically acceptable at the societal and individual level, that we actually have to

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:46.520
[Guest]: take a few use cases and maybe talk about it, right. So for example, getting rid of

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:51.080
[Guest]: Down syndrome is a straightforward case. I mean, I don't think a lot of people will come

00:52:51.080 --> 00:52:57.200
[Guest]: and say that no, you shouldn't do gene editing. Getting fairer skin though, for your child

00:52:57.200 --> 00:53:03.200
[Guest]: is slightly more tricky. Because we don't know what kind of advantages that you're conferring

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:08.080
[Guest]: the child if the child was not fair skin, probably, in terms of social perception, there

00:53:08.080 --> 00:53:13.640
[Guest]: might be a difference. But in terms of health, there might not be a perceptible change, right.

00:53:13.640 --> 00:53:18.600
[Guest]: But at the same time, would we just have like a society of fair skin children, because we

00:53:18.600 --> 00:53:23.440
[Guest]: think that fairer skin is better looking or something like that? I mean, the ethical questions

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:27.320
[Guest]: that that are associated with that are very, very different.

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:31.160
[Amit Varma]: And it's kind of also straightforward, sort of, again, like I said, individual liberty

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:35.640
[Amit Varma]: and a whole more community way of thinking, for example, let's say a parent wants fair

00:53:35.640 --> 00:53:41.720
[Amit Varma]: skin. And they might well argue that it's not for other people to judge, well, you know,

00:53:41.720 --> 00:53:44.680
[Amit Varma]: the value of fair skin and make those trade offs. I'm the parent, I'll make it in the

00:53:44.680 --> 00:53:51.440
[Amit Varma]: same same way that I could teach my kid a math instead of drawing, or I could send my

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:57.240
[Amit Varma]: kid to drawing classes instead of physics classes. And you know, all that is up to me

00:53:57.240 --> 00:54:01.160
[Amit Varma]: and they will enhance the kid in different ways, there'll be different characteristics.

00:54:01.160 --> 00:54:09.360
[Amit Varma]: So I get to choose why shouldn't I and that's kind of a difficult argument to sort of counter

00:54:09.360 --> 00:54:14.360
[Amit Varma]: and especially if, you know, you and I would both be agreed that, you know, that it's not

00:54:14.360 --> 00:54:19.200
[Amit Varma]: good for society, definitely, if people display this kind of preferences, because then it

00:54:19.200 --> 00:54:25.880
[Amit Varma]: affects, you know, people with darker skins and perspectives just change and it will aggravate

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:31.720
[Guest]: what we see as societal inequalities for some time. If they persist, I think we might just

00:54:31.720 --> 00:54:36.880
[Guest]: end up with a completely fair skin society. And that would probably mark the end of humanity.

00:54:36.880 --> 00:54:41.320
[Guest]: Because the minute we all become genetically one, that is it, I mean, as a species, we

00:54:41.320 --> 00:54:46.240
[Guest]: are dead. So we have to guard against that in a way, but that doesn't actually trample

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:51.880
[Guest]: on on individual liberties. And that is something I think we have not come to grasp yet. The

00:54:51.880 --> 00:54:58.360
[Guest]: idea that having fair skin children, or allowing that kind of gene editing is good or not is

00:54:58.360 --> 00:55:02.720
[Guest]: something that we have not understood it because there's an economic argument to this as well.

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:09.320
[Guest]: Gene editing currently costs a few billion dollars to do in one person. We are not, a

00:55:09.320 --> 00:55:12.800
[Guest]: lot of people in India are not going to be able to afford that. People who can afford

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:19.440
[Guest]: that might actually prefer these kind of luxurious, recreative gene editing therapies. Simply

00:55:19.440 --> 00:55:24.960
[Guest]: by allowing them to do those, we might bring down the cost of gene editing total. And then

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:29.560
[Guest]: gene editing for disease alleviation might become cheaper, which will actually impact

00:55:29.560 --> 00:55:35.360
[Guest]: a lot of the poor people, vulnerable people who need access to gene therapeutics. So when

00:55:35.360 --> 00:55:38.960
[Guest]: we think about the morality of doing some of these actions, we also have to think about

00:55:38.960 --> 00:55:44.720
[Guest]: the impact that has on the access of those therapies to people who really need them.

00:55:44.720 --> 00:55:49.680
[Amit Varma]: I'll come up with two thoughts here. One is, for example, let's for a moment leave genetics

00:55:49.680 --> 00:55:53.800
[Amit Varma]: aside, if you're talking about individual choices, and what role the state should play

00:55:53.800 --> 00:55:59.300
[Amit Varma]: in regulating them. Let's take another example from outside science, where if individuals

00:55:59.300 --> 00:56:04.520
[Amit Varma]: make rational choices, it ends up with bad social outcomes and talk about what the different

00:56:04.520 --> 00:56:08.560
[Amit Varma]: schools of thought would have been. What I have in mind, for example, is I live in Mumbai.

00:56:08.560 --> 00:56:12.680
[Amit Varma]: Now, in Mumbai, it is very common, and every once in a while, somebody will do a feature

00:56:12.680 --> 00:56:18.680
[Amit Varma]: on how landlords are not giving houses to, say, particular communities, or to single

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:24.320
[Amit Varma]: women, and so on and so forth. Now, at a social level, it's a huge problem, because it leads

00:56:24.320 --> 00:56:28.060
[Amit Varma]: to ghettoization. And it doesn't lead to the kind of intermingling you would like to see

00:56:28.060 --> 00:56:33.420
[Amit Varma]: though, by and large, Mumbai is a very cosmopolitan city, but you have these sort of enclaves

00:56:33.420 --> 00:56:37.780
[Amit Varma]: and and that's not a nice thing. However, at an individual level, it is up to every

00:56:37.780 --> 00:56:42.740
[Amit Varma]: individual who they want to give their house to. So if you have a Jan landlord who decides

00:56:42.740 --> 00:56:47.100
[Amit Varma]: that I don't want non vegetarian people in my house, although I am non vegetarian, and

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:52.460
[Amit Varma]: I would not get that flat, I respect his right over his own property. Others would argue

00:56:52.460 --> 00:56:57.340
[Amit Varma]: that so the argument for state coercion would be that this is a social problem, the state

00:56:57.340 --> 00:57:03.220
[Amit Varma]: has to step in and make such discrimination illegal, to which my argument would be that

00:57:03.220 --> 00:57:06.860
[Amit Varma]: you don't have state capacity to enforce it. And how do you know why a person is not giving

00:57:06.860 --> 00:57:11.020
[Amit Varma]: a house to someone. So the law is completely pointless. But even if it wasn't, and even

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:15.620
[Amit Varma]: if you could enforce it, I would argue that you can't you shouldn't do it. Because state

00:57:15.620 --> 00:57:20.820
[Amit Varma]: coercion should be used very sparingly. And certain social problems can only be solved

00:57:20.820 --> 00:57:25.900
[Amit Varma]: by society itself. And what you want is over time, you know, the solutions to them have

00:57:25.900 --> 00:57:31.780
[Amit Varma]: to lie within the realms of civil society and within the culture itself. To set the

00:57:31.780 --> 00:57:37.860
[Amit Varma]: precedent of the state coercing on the basis of imposing some notion of virtue is very

00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:41.980
[Amit Varma]: dangerous because today they might do it to support your notion of notion of virtue, but

00:57:41.980 --> 00:57:47.020
[Amit Varma]: tomorrow it could be some other notion. So defending individual liberty is a better idea.

00:57:47.020 --> 00:57:50.900
[Amit Varma]: And this thought came to me when you were, you know, talking about, for example, that

00:57:50.900 --> 00:57:56.260
[Amit Varma]: thorny notion of what do we do if people sort of go for fair skin kids. And and my thought

00:57:56.260 --> 00:58:00.620
[Amit Varma]: there again would be that this is a social problem. I'd be very worried if the state

00:58:00.620 --> 00:58:03.700
[Amit Varma]: stepped in to decide what can and cannot be selected for.

00:58:03.700 --> 00:58:09.460
[Guest]: Exactly. It is a social problem. And my fear is that gene editing might become a way for

00:58:09.460 --> 00:58:13.380
[Guest]: the society to kind of say, okay, we have gene editing, we can fix all problems using

00:58:13.380 --> 00:58:18.420
[Guest]: that. And instead of going to the root of the problem and trying to figure out why do

00:58:18.420 --> 00:58:22.900
[Guest]: people prefer fair skin to begin with, and the fact that it makes no sense, and that

00:58:22.900 --> 00:58:27.620
[Guest]: we as a society can change our perception of the way people of the way we feel about

00:58:27.620 --> 00:58:34.020
[Guest]: people and the way they look. And that is the crux of the problem. But we might just

00:58:34.020 --> 00:58:37.780
[Guest]: not look at it at all and just say, okay, now we have something that can magically change

00:58:37.780 --> 00:58:41.980
[Guest]: everybody to fair skin, which would be utter nonsense.

00:58:41.980 --> 00:58:45.940
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And the other thought that strikes me, and I'd say this question for later, but since

00:58:45.940 --> 00:58:50.940
[Amit Varma]: it comes up now is a question of inequality, where, you know, I would say that I do not

00:58:50.940 --> 00:58:54.620
[Amit Varma]: foresee that can be a problem. Because when new technologies come up, a lot of people

00:58:54.620 --> 00:58:59.020
[Amit Varma]: assume because there's new technologies at the start at the gestation period, especially

00:58:59.020 --> 00:59:02.640
[Amit Varma]: are incredibly expensive. They assume that they will cause inequality, only the rich

00:59:02.640 --> 00:59:07.420
[Amit Varma]: can afford it. And they'll create a gap between themselves and the poor. But the way I see

00:59:07.420 --> 00:59:11.780
[Amit Varma]: it is, if you look at something like smartphones, for example, everybody has smartphones rather

00:59:11.780 --> 00:59:16.020
[Amit Varma]: than increase inequalities, they have decreased them, they have equalize the field, they spread

00:59:16.020 --> 00:59:21.060
[Amit Varma]: opportunities to everyone. Similarly, I would imagine with over time with over scale as

00:59:21.060 --> 00:59:25.340
[Amit Varma]: more and more research happens, you will also like you know, like we like you mentioned

00:59:25.340 --> 00:59:29.780
[Amit Varma]: earlier that the human genome project, sequencing cost billions of dollars, and now it's there

00:59:29.780 --> 00:59:34.740
[Amit Varma]: for $100. And similarly, whatever technologies come up for gene editing or whatever someday

00:59:34.740 --> 00:59:39.200
[Amit Varma]: will be affordable by the common person, which is an incredible thing, because what they

00:59:39.200 --> 00:59:43.940
[Amit Varma]: are most likely to be used for most of the time is to solve diseases and illnesses and

00:59:43.940 --> 00:59:49.460
[Amit Varma]: so on. And the amount of human misery that will be alleviated, you cannot put a value

00:59:49.460 --> 00:59:50.460
[Guest]: to that.

00:59:50.460 --> 00:59:56.100
[Guest]: I mean, scientifically speaking, the lowest hanging fruit is disease alleviation, right?

00:59:56.100 --> 01:00:00.820
[Guest]: Because a lot of genetic diseases particularly are caused by a single mutation. It is easy

01:00:00.820 --> 01:00:05.340
[Guest]: for us to do the cut and paste maneuver for a single thing and everything else in the

01:00:05.340 --> 01:00:10.760
[Guest]: body functions normally. The more genes that are involved in thing in a particular characteristic,

01:00:10.760 --> 01:00:15.920
[Guest]: the more complicated that cut and paste goes. And so, it is the less the more difficult

01:00:15.920 --> 01:00:21.860
[Guest]: it is for us to actually get away with doing CRISPR. Intelligence, for example, there have

01:00:21.860 --> 01:00:25.660
[Guest]: been a lot of reports that oh, we are going to have these designer babies and super soldiers

01:00:25.660 --> 01:00:30.940
[Guest]: and extremely intelligent beings. We simply do not understand the genetics behind intelligence.

01:00:30.940 --> 01:00:36.740
[Guest]: So, the idea that we might actually opt for more intelligent babies is kind of...

01:00:36.740 --> 01:00:42.060
[Amit Varma]: And it depends on how you define intelligence. Like, if you define a certain kind of pattern

01:00:42.060 --> 01:00:45.860
[Amit Varma]: recognition and so on as intelligence, and you could even select for autism, for example.

01:00:45.860 --> 01:00:50.380
[Amit Varma]: So, it depends on, you know, I mean, it is true that a lot of intelligence, however you

01:00:50.380 --> 01:00:56.700
[Amit Varma]: define it is encoded in the gene, some scientists estimate, I think up to 60% is kind of the

01:00:56.700 --> 01:01:00.020
[Amit Varma]: consensus, but a lot of it is nurture. It's again nature and nurture working together

01:01:00.020 --> 01:01:05.740
[Amit Varma]: and one is not sure how to define it or what value to place upon it. I want to ask one

01:01:05.740 --> 01:01:09.780
[Amit Varma]: last question about ethics, because I had taken a stand on this many, many years ago

01:01:09.780 --> 01:01:13.380
[Amit Varma]: with a very controversial article. So, I'll ask your opinion on that. Before we get to

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:17.540
[Amit Varma]: politics and eugenics, which I think, you know, all of that, the political implications

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:21.740
[Amit Varma]: of it, which you had referred to earlier, and I think we should examine in more detail.

01:01:21.740 --> 01:01:26.340
[Amit Varma]: And my question is really about gene doping. And this came up some 12 years ago. And my

01:01:26.340 --> 01:01:30.220
[Amit Varma]: sense was that it should not be called gene doping. And that gene doping should in fact

01:01:30.220 --> 01:01:33.780
[Amit Varma]: be allowed. Because my whole point was that look, we are taking protein shakes, we are

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:38.460
[Amit Varma]: going to the gym, we are training in high altitudes, we are doing all kinds of things

01:01:38.460 --> 01:01:44.140
[Amit Varma]: to optimise our ability for sport. So why not do that? Why not extend that to genetics?

01:01:44.140 --> 01:01:49.740
[Amit Varma]: Why do you draw a line there? And my second point was that look, in any case, it is not

01:01:49.740 --> 01:01:55.100
[Amit Varma]: that gene doping will spoil a level playing field. On the other hand, sports depends on

01:01:55.100 --> 01:01:59.900
[Amit Varma]: the playing field not being leveled. Every single sportsman has a genetic advantage that

01:01:59.900 --> 01:02:05.140
[Amit Varma]: allows him to get there. It's obviously a combination of inborn talent and hard work.

01:02:05.140 --> 01:02:10.820
[Amit Varma]: But without those inborn advantages, like how much oxygen your lungs can take, or so

01:02:10.820 --> 01:02:15.820
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth, you know, all elite sportsmen are basically freaks of nature in a genetic

01:02:15.820 --> 01:02:20.780
[Amit Varma]: sense, complete outliers in some way or the other. And what gene doping actually allows

01:02:20.780 --> 01:02:26.420
[Amit Varma]: you to do is level the field a little bit. So I don't really see an ethical problem with

01:02:26.420 --> 01:02:31.020
[Amit Varma]: it, per se, quite apart from the logistical issues of can you even detect it if it happens.

01:02:31.020 --> 01:02:32.540
[Guest]: But what's your take on this?

01:02:32.540 --> 01:02:39.140
[Guest]: Yeah, you're right. A lot of, at least the most elite athletes seem to have some kind

01:02:39.140 --> 01:02:43.700
[Guest]: of genetic inheritance that they can be proud of. Most recently, we spoke about Michael

01:02:43.700 --> 01:02:49.660
[Guest]: Phelps and his ability to process lactic acid faster. And so he tires less because his body

01:02:49.660 --> 01:02:51.340
[Guest]: doesn't make that much lactic acid.

01:02:51.340 --> 01:02:53.900
[Amit Varma]: Common with many elite cyclists as well.

01:02:53.900 --> 01:02:59.900
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah. Then there was this family, I think in Norway, which has got a muscle, it's

01:02:59.900 --> 01:03:04.580
[Guest]: a family inherited mutation, which causes high muscular strength. So everyone in the

01:03:04.580 --> 01:03:05.580
[Amit Varma]: family are really...

01:03:05.580 --> 01:03:09.780
[Amit Varma]: I think I was reading about this. There are 29 people in that family who have that thing

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:12.860
[Guest]: and many of them are sportsmen at the highest level.

01:03:12.860 --> 01:03:17.060
[Guest]: So it does occur. And obviously, we can really counter the fact, because naturally or not.

01:03:17.060 --> 01:03:21.620
[Guest]: And I think you're right. I mean, I don't see why we should stop people from... Actually,

01:03:21.620 --> 01:03:29.380
[Guest]: I don't know. I have to think about this. Because if I was born with a mutation, that

01:03:29.380 --> 01:03:35.820
[Guest]: allowed me to be better at a sport or have better endurance to actually follow sport,

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:41.460
[Guest]: I might from my childhood be put in an environment where hard work is required. But if I have

01:03:41.460 --> 01:03:45.780
[Guest]: access to a mutation that kind of takes away the hard work component from it...

01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:49.820
[Guest]: But it can't, right? A mutation can just get you up to the natural level of the other person.

01:03:49.820 --> 01:03:53.160
[Guest]: As long as it doesn't take away from the hard work component, I don't see why it's a problem.

01:03:53.160 --> 01:03:57.660
[Guest]: If we figure out at some point of time, the magic to do away with hard work, then I think

01:03:57.660 --> 01:03:58.660
[Amit Varma]: we might have a problem.

01:03:58.660 --> 01:04:02.620
[Amit Varma]: Oh, and the interesting thing is, if you ban gene doping, but you allow gene therapies

01:04:02.620 --> 01:04:06.940
[Amit Varma]: in the population, then what you'll have is that everyone in the population can be a Michael

01:04:06.940 --> 01:04:09.420
[Amit Varma]: Phelps, but not a swimmer, not a competitive swimmer.

01:04:09.420 --> 01:04:16.420
[Guest]: I think eventually sports might be the biggest victim of gene editing. I mean, if you're

01:04:16.420 --> 01:04:24.620
[Guest]: not consciously either allow gene doping or ban it and monitor it meticulously, the whole

01:04:24.620 --> 01:04:28.620
[Guest]: idea of Olympics and elite sports is probably just going to become redundant.

01:04:28.620 --> 01:04:32.580
[Amit Varma]: Because all sports at some level are based on inequality. Some people get the luck of

01:04:32.580 --> 01:04:37.380
[Amit Varma]: the draw. They have the privilege of being born with these immense skills. And I actually,

01:04:37.380 --> 01:04:40.100
[Amit Varma]: because I love sport, I want that to continue that sense.

01:04:40.100 --> 01:04:44.980
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there's there's no ethical reason I can think of for sort of banning

01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:49.780
[Amit Varma]: gene editing, even banning gene doping, even if it were possible. And again, it's a function

01:04:49.780 --> 01:04:54.500
[Unknown]: of the way the words plays, like calling it gene doping itself is making a value judgment

01:04:54.500 --> 01:04:55.500
[Unknown]: on it.

01:04:55.500 --> 01:05:00.100
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of get to the politics, like the reason genetics gets a bad rap.

01:05:00.100 --> 01:05:04.940
[Amit Varma]: And the reason that even today, it's almost politically incorrect in many places to speak

01:05:04.940 --> 01:05:10.420
[Amit Varma]: of this or that trait being inherited, especially something like intelligence, for example,

01:05:10.420 --> 01:05:15.060
[Amit Varma]: is what it has been used for, what genetics has been used for. And in fact, you spoke

01:05:15.060 --> 01:05:20.780
[Amit Varma]: of eugenics. Eugenics was popular in both the US and the English among left wing intellectuals

01:05:20.780 --> 01:05:25.340
[Amit Varma]: like George Bernard Shaw and so on, because, you know, they had that transformative vision

01:05:25.340 --> 01:05:29.700
[Amit Varma]: of a better society. And then of course, Hitler used it in the way he did. So it's not some

01:05:29.700 --> 01:05:36.380
[Amit Varma]: right wing fascist thing, it kind of spread across. And what can kind of seem to happen

01:05:36.380 --> 01:05:43.300
[Amit Varma]: there to me is that the political associate the negative association of eugenics, the

01:05:43.300 --> 01:05:49.980
[Amit Varma]: way it was used, has cast a bad light upon the field of genetics, which I think is unfair,

01:05:49.980 --> 01:05:56.820
[Amit Varma]: because I think people don't often make the distinction between description and prescription.

01:05:56.820 --> 01:06:02.180
[Amit Varma]: And today, what has happened is, if you are to say that, for example, A and B are not

01:06:02.180 --> 01:06:07.940
[Amit Varma]: the same, that is a description, it is not a prescription that they be treated differently.

01:06:07.940 --> 01:06:11.860
[Amit Varma]: And this conflation often happens in the public domain. What's your sense of this?

01:06:11.860 --> 01:06:19.220
[Guest]: Interesting. So for my for the Labcoats podcast, I had I had interviewed someone for rare diseases.

01:06:19.220 --> 01:06:24.780
[Guest]: And February is rare diseases month. And even that segment, and this is a clinician scientist,

01:06:24.780 --> 01:06:29.340
[Guest]: and even that segment ended with him saying about that this is not eugenics, right, that

01:06:29.340 --> 01:06:34.180
[Guest]: gene therapies for rare diseases is not eugenics. So there is this fear, not just among civilians,

01:06:34.180 --> 01:06:39.140
[Guest]: but even people who are actually very intimate with the field, that are we crossing a boundary

01:06:39.140 --> 01:06:43.620
[Guest]: of eugenics? I mean, truth be told, eugenics is the idea that we want better children.

01:06:43.620 --> 01:06:49.060
[Guest]: I mean, that that is the basic essence of the idea that you want your child to have

01:06:49.060 --> 01:06:51.660
[Guest]: the best resources that they can.

01:06:51.660 --> 01:06:55.100
[Amit Varma]: But that's the original meaning of the term, if you accept that language evolves, what

01:06:55.100 --> 01:06:59.780
[Amit Varma]: eugenic basically means today in the popular imagination, is you're trying to reshape society

01:06:59.780 --> 01:07:01.100
[Guest]: through coercive means.

01:07:01.100 --> 01:07:08.580
[Guest]: I think that is basically the point that we need to make is that we all want better societies.

01:07:08.580 --> 01:07:17.020
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean we kill off what we deem to be bad eggs. It just means that we

01:07:17.020 --> 01:07:24.260
[Guest]: either, we redefine ourselves to be a society which is more homogeneous, and more acceptable.

01:07:24.260 --> 01:07:27.180
[Guest]: We do not say that everything has to come in binaries, we do not say that...

01:07:27.180 --> 01:07:28.180
[Amit Varma]: More heterogeneous, you mean?

01:07:28.180 --> 01:07:33.140
[Guest]: Yeah, sorry, more heterogeneous. Yeah. Not everything has to come in a binary. Men can

01:07:33.140 --> 01:07:34.940
[Amit Varma]: like men, if they want to.

01:07:34.940 --> 01:07:39.020
[Amit Varma]: And not everybody has to have any kind of value judgment on it. You are like this, therefore

01:07:39.020 --> 01:07:40.020
[Guest]: you are bad.

01:07:40.020 --> 01:07:44.340
[Guest]: Yeah. So, so that is the first thing we really need to figure out. And then the second thing

01:07:44.340 --> 01:07:50.060
[Guest]: is that what genetic editing allows us to do is, if there are diseases that we think

01:07:50.060 --> 01:07:56.060
[Guest]: are particularly debilitating to somebody, they can have the option of choosing a healthier

01:07:56.060 --> 01:08:01.700
[Guest]: life. So, we are in no way saying that you are bad. It is like taking medicine. I mean,

01:08:01.700 --> 01:08:06.460
[Guest]: if you have a fever, obviously you're going to take paracetamol. You're not going to sit

01:08:06.460 --> 01:08:10.020
[Guest]: and say, oh, I've got fever. I'm different from my family members because they don't

01:08:10.020 --> 01:08:13.860
[Guest]: have fever, I have fever, there's nothing I can do in life. And nobody is, again, attaching

01:08:13.860 --> 01:08:15.780
[Guest]: a value judgment to the fact that you have fever.

01:08:15.780 --> 01:08:21.060
[Guest]: I have this entire problem with a lot of mental health diseases, for example, is that we put

01:08:21.060 --> 01:08:26.900
[Guest]: this stigma on to mental health diseases, which are probably also genetically linked,

01:08:26.900 --> 01:08:31.820
[Guest]: in a way which is very different from any physical disease that you see, right. And

01:08:31.820 --> 01:08:35.940
[Guest]: because of that, they are stuck in a corner and they're not able to progress. What genetic

01:08:35.940 --> 01:08:40.820
[Guest]: editing allows us now to do is just a better understanding of gene functions, a better

01:08:40.820 --> 01:08:45.980
[Guest]: understanding of how diseases are caused, and a better ability to accept and treat them.

01:08:45.980 --> 01:08:51.140
[Guest]: And we are now at that time in society where we can decide that, okay, we have the ability

01:08:51.140 --> 01:08:56.340
[Guest]: to do all of this. Should we do it? Should we decide to make ourselves better in a more

01:08:56.340 --> 01:09:00.980
[Guest]: progressive way? Should we be scared of our history, not learn from it and say, either

01:09:00.980 --> 01:09:03.580
[Guest]: look at our history, learn from it and go, no, no, we don't want to go down this route

01:09:03.580 --> 01:09:08.460
[Guest]: at all, because this might mess up. Or look at it and say, okay, we have made mistakes

01:09:08.460 --> 01:09:15.100
[Guest]: in the past. But now there's a new technology that can allow us to do things better. So

01:09:15.100 --> 01:09:16.100
[Guest]: should we take that chance?

01:09:16.100 --> 01:09:21.300
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in the words of Adam Cohen, who wrote in an editorial in the LA Times a couple of

01:09:21.300 --> 01:09:25.660
[Amit Varma]: years back, where he said that eugenics was a war on the weak, but now what is happening

01:09:25.660 --> 01:09:30.860
[Amit Varma]: in gene editing can be a war for the weak. So that has, you know, immense connotations

01:09:30.860 --> 01:09:37.780
[Amit Varma]: of virtue. And the way I look at it is that the way the difference between eugenics and,

01:09:37.780 --> 01:09:42.220
[Amit Varma]: you know, the sort of gene editing that you and I support is that the kind of gene editing

01:09:42.220 --> 01:09:46.060
[Amit Varma]: that you and I support make the lives of individuals better. They have individual aims. They don't

01:09:46.060 --> 01:09:51.460
[Amit Varma]: have communal aims that we must have a pure race or we must reshape society. And that's

01:09:51.460 --> 01:09:55.940
[Amit Varma]: yeah, that's the second point that they are voluntary and not coercive. So as long as

01:09:55.940 --> 01:09:59.580
[Amit Varma]: they are voluntary, I don't have an issue with it. The moment they become coercive,

01:09:59.580 --> 01:10:04.020
[Amit Varma]: it's just flat out wrong and no other detail, frankly, matters to me. So tell me something

01:10:04.020 --> 01:10:09.060
[Amit Varma]: in this field of science, particularly, it seems to me that politics is always hovering

01:10:09.060 --> 01:10:12.620
[Amit Varma]: in the background, especially because of all the things that has happened, does it get

01:10:12.620 --> 01:10:17.700
[Amit Varma]: in the way of the science, for example, just, you know, the question of intelligence has

01:10:17.700 --> 01:10:23.420
[Amit Varma]: been so politicized, does it get in the way of what scientists research and what they

01:10:23.420 --> 01:10:29.220
[Amit Varma]: say, you know, is a scientist who is choosing between subject A and subject B some in a

01:10:29.220 --> 01:10:34.380
[Amit Varma]: university somewhere, going to think that no subject A could be controversial, because my descriptive

01:10:34.380 --> 01:10:39.620
[Amit Varma]: words could be misinterpreted as prescriptive, and I could get into a controversy. So let

01:10:39.620 --> 01:10:43.700
[Amit Varma]: me do subject B, do things like that happen? Does that affect the science?

01:10:43.700 --> 01:10:49.180
[Guest]: Particularly in India, I don't think for gene editing in India per se, I don't think that

01:10:49.180 --> 01:10:51.380
[Guest]: has happened. Because

01:10:51.380 --> 01:10:52.820
[Amit Varma]: It's not such a big thing here yet.

01:10:52.820 --> 01:10:56.740
[Guest]: It is not a big thing. The guidelines have been written by scientists, not by policymakers

01:10:56.740 --> 01:11:01.220
[Guest]: or politicians. Our problem is that we have always looked westwards while forming our

01:11:01.220 --> 01:11:06.180
[Guest]: own policies. So we have not looked at gene editing as an opportunity at all. We have

01:11:06.180 --> 01:11:12.940
[Guest]: not thought about the fact that we are 1.3 billion people with a range of say rare diseases,

01:11:12.940 --> 01:11:21.220
[Guest]: other genetic diseases, mosquito-borne diseases, that could provide an opportunity for us to

01:11:21.220 --> 01:11:26.820
[Guest]: be world leaders in gene editing therapies. Instead, we are looking westward and saying

01:11:26.820 --> 01:11:33.300
[Guest]: that, okay, what is the West doing? Is heritable gene editing acceptable? No, then it's not

01:11:33.300 --> 01:11:39.700
[Guest]: acceptable to us as well. I don't think we have figured out why scientists from, say,

01:11:39.700 --> 01:11:44.140
[Guest]: the US Academy of Sciences or the UK Academy are saying that, actually only the US, I don't

01:11:44.140 --> 01:11:50.140
[Guest]: think UK Academies has said nothing, has commented on heritable gene editing, but the US Academy

01:11:50.140 --> 01:11:55.980
[Guest]: and the European Academy has come across and strongly said that germline gene editing is

01:11:55.980 --> 01:12:02.380
[Guest]: unethical. And so it is banned in India as well. I don't think we have figured out whether

01:12:02.380 --> 01:12:06.980
[Guest]: Indian citizens think that this is unethical or unethical. I don't think we have even bothered

01:12:06.980 --> 01:12:07.980
[Amit Varma]: to ask.

01:12:07.980 --> 01:12:12.500
[Amit Varma]: We'll come to the policy domain a little bit later. Another question that I think falls

01:12:12.500 --> 01:12:17.300
[Amit Varma]: within the realm of the ethical is, and something that you brought up earlier, is a question

01:12:17.300 --> 01:12:22.900
[Amit Varma]: of diversity, in that if within a society you have sort of certain, like the preference

01:12:22.900 --> 01:12:26.700
[Amit Varma]: of fair skin, and the danger with something like the preference for fair skin is that

01:12:26.700 --> 01:12:30.940
[Amit Varma]: it could set off an arms race towards people getting fairer and fairer skin till everyone

01:12:30.940 --> 01:12:35.340
[Amit Varma]: is fair skin and that affects diversity. And that's just one example being fair skin, but

01:12:35.340 --> 01:12:40.380
[Amit Varma]: there could be other examples of the way people behave and all of that, assuming that at some

01:12:40.380 --> 01:12:44.180
[Amit Varma]: point in time, the science reaches a stage which it undoubtedly will, it's only a matter

01:12:44.180 --> 01:12:47.860
[Amit Varma]: of time that you can basically select for everything. And sort of when that happens,

01:12:47.860 --> 01:12:53.820
[Amit Varma]: there is a danger that we move towards homogeneity. For example, I had done an episode with Vikram

01:12:53.820 --> 01:12:58.580
[Amit Varma]: Doctor on Indian food and how most of it is actually not Indian. And one example he gave

01:12:58.580 --> 01:13:02.980
[Amit Varma]: there was of the banana, which basically India exported to the world. And we have a whole

01:13:02.980 --> 01:13:08.220
[Amit Varma]: huge range of indigenous bananas. But what happened was for all kinds of reasons of economics

01:13:08.220 --> 01:13:13.180
[Amit Varma]: and scale and whatever, one particular tasteless kind of banana called the Cavendish banana

01:13:13.180 --> 01:13:18.420
[Amit Varma]: became popular everywhere. And now that is being sort of exported back to India, where

01:13:18.420 --> 01:13:23.340
[Amit Varma]: it is overwhelming the other indigenous kinds of bananas. So and you know, could something

01:13:23.340 --> 01:13:27.980
[Amit Varma]: like this, for example, happen with human beings? Because as a geneticist, diversity

01:13:27.980 --> 01:13:28.980
[Guest]: is great, isn't it?

01:13:28.980 --> 01:13:35.220
[Guest]: Yeah, it is great. And it's needed for survival of any species. So the idea that we might

01:13:35.220 --> 01:13:39.660
[Guest]: have this preference of having a cricket team with all Virat Kohli's is going to be a nightmare,

01:13:39.660 --> 01:13:44.380
[Guest]: right? I mean, we can't all be Virat Kohli. We shouldn't all be Virat Kohli. We need the

01:13:44.380 --> 01:13:47.980
[Amit Varma]: other players, right? We need a well-behaved Virat Kohli. We would like Hardik Pandey to

01:13:47.980 --> 01:13:50.020
[Amit Varma]: come back as soon as possible, preferably.

01:13:50.020 --> 01:13:55.860
[Amit Varma]: You are saying this? Okay. No, because Hardik is kind of politically incorrect for people

01:13:55.860 --> 01:14:00.220
[Amit Varma]: to say good things about after that sort of kerfuffle he had on the...

01:14:00.220 --> 01:14:05.060
[Guest]: Of course. And again, I'm not going to judge him as the person, but he is an all-rounder

01:14:05.060 --> 01:14:09.220
[Guest]: and we need an all-rounder in the team. And then it's up to the team to make sure that

01:14:09.220 --> 01:14:10.220
[Guest]: the all-rounder is well-behaved.

01:14:10.220 --> 01:14:14.340
[Amit Varma]: Cool. We shall do a high five right after this session, because I think he's a very

01:14:14.340 --> 01:14:18.820
[Amit Varma]: fine player and underrated player and a much better batsman than he gets credit for, which

01:14:18.820 --> 01:14:23.700
[Amit Varma]: distinguishes him from our other great bowling all-rounder, Kapil Dev. What are the sort

01:14:23.700 --> 01:14:30.980
[Amit Varma]: of malicious uses of the deliberate malicious uses? I'm not talking about unintended consequences,

01:14:30.980 --> 01:14:35.020
[Amit Varma]: which I'll come to and we need to discuss mosquitoes and bats. But what are the sort

01:14:35.020 --> 01:14:39.620
[Amit Varma]: of malicious uses? Like right now, we are recording this on Jan 25th. And there's this

01:14:39.620 --> 01:14:43.980
[Amit Varma]: corona virus thing that is happening somewhere in China. And you were telling me earlier

01:14:43.980 --> 01:14:48.220
[Amit Varma]: while we were having carbs over lunch that there's a possibility that something that

01:14:48.220 --> 01:14:52.340
[Amit Varma]: was being, you know, bioweapons might have been created in labs and something has escaped

01:14:52.340 --> 01:14:53.340
[Amit Varma]: from there.

01:14:53.340 --> 01:15:00.500
[Guest]: That is the effect of carbs. So there is a lab in Wuhan, which is a biosafety containment

01:15:00.500 --> 01:15:05.980
[Guest]: lab, where they were researching the SARS virus from 2003. At this point of time, there

01:15:05.980 --> 01:15:11.860
[Guest]: is absolutely no link between the viruses that they were studying and the incident that

01:15:11.860 --> 01:15:20.300
[Guest]: happened at the Wuhan seafood market. But the use of gene editing to create and engineer

01:15:20.300 --> 01:15:26.220
[Guest]: such viruses exists, right. We can use gene editing to take a virus, say even something

01:15:26.220 --> 01:15:33.660
[Guest]: as simple as measles, which is common in India, you can take measles virus and turn it to

01:15:33.660 --> 01:15:39.500
[Guest]: be vaccine resistant and let it back out, right. Those are things that are really, really

01:15:39.500 --> 01:15:46.220
[Guest]: scary that are possible. And virus, the genomes are sometimes publicly available. There's

01:15:46.220 --> 01:15:51.500
[Guest]: this field of biology known as synthetic biology, where you create the entire organism out of

01:15:51.500 --> 01:15:59.560
[Guest]: scratch. And it was in 2002, that scientists made the first poliovirus out of scratch.

01:15:59.560 --> 01:16:04.900
[Guest]: And they put the sequence out in public domain, which basically meant that anybody couldn't

01:16:04.900 --> 01:16:09.140
[Guest]: go and see on how to create a poliovirus. And that was subsequently brought down. And

01:16:09.140 --> 01:16:14.300
[Guest]: now the public knowledge of some, at least some viruses is banned. So you don't want

01:16:14.300 --> 01:16:20.860
[Guest]: to put things like this out in the public domain. But CRISPR has now become so universal.

01:16:20.860 --> 01:16:24.820
[Guest]: And it's every lab in the institution I used to work previously has done gene editing in

01:16:24.820 --> 01:16:30.700
[Guest]: some form or the other by now. So the knowledge has become so, so universal that it is easier

01:16:30.700 --> 01:16:36.460
[Guest]: for people who want to use it maliciously to now use it and create something dangerous.

01:16:36.460 --> 01:16:41.700
[Guest]: And it might not take a lot of effort to do that. Whether they have the standards to be

01:16:41.700 --> 01:16:45.540
[Guest]: able to protect themselves from that is an entirely different thing. But A, the science

01:16:45.540 --> 01:16:50.900
[Guest]: has become universal. And B, there has been an increased attention at bioweapons again,

01:16:50.900 --> 01:16:55.980
[Guest]: mainly because the whole idea of genome editing, creating these kind of bioweapons was first

01:16:55.980 --> 01:17:02.420
[Guest]: flagged in a US intelligence agency report in 2016. And subsequently, a lot of other

01:17:02.420 --> 01:17:06.460
[Guest]: countries have put up notices that this might actually become reality. And I just think

01:17:06.460 --> 01:17:11.100
[Guest]: the renewed attention to the topic itself might have made it more appealing to non-state

01:17:11.100 --> 01:17:16.740
[Guest]: actors as well. That states now think that this is achievable. So maybe it is.

01:17:16.740 --> 01:17:20.820
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, that's like earlier people used to be worried about nuclear power. And, you

01:17:20.820 --> 01:17:25.300
[Amit Varma]: know, you used to talk about suitcase nukes. But obviously, suitcase nukes are technically

01:17:25.300 --> 01:17:30.140
[Amit Varma]: very, very hard to actually manufacture. Two guys sitting in a garage lab somewhere can't

01:17:30.140 --> 01:17:34.420
[Amit Varma]: do it. The materials are expensive, uranium, proteinium, whatever. So is what you're saying

01:17:34.420 --> 01:17:40.620
[Amit Varma]: that, for example, you know, is it far easier and far less resource incentive to manufacture

01:17:40.620 --> 01:17:42.020
[Guest]: a virus, for example, in a lab?

01:17:42.020 --> 01:17:45.500
[Guest]: It would be as compared to the other weapons. It depends entirely on the desperation of

01:17:45.500 --> 01:17:49.340
[Guest]: the people trying to create that kind of a weapon. And as we have seen in the past decades,

01:17:49.340 --> 01:17:53.700
[Guest]: we have become more and more stricter on the other weapon systems, right? And it's far

01:17:53.700 --> 01:17:56.060
[Amit Varma]: easier to track nuclear weapons.

01:17:56.060 --> 01:17:57.060
[Amit Varma]: This we can't control.

01:17:57.060 --> 01:17:59.060
[Amit Varma]: This we can't control. This we really can't track.

01:17:59.060 --> 01:18:03.060
[Amit Varma]: Like, hypothetically, if someone was to come to you and offer you some money, which would

01:18:03.060 --> 01:18:07.300
[Amit Varma]: make you inclined to do whatever they wanted you to do, and they offered you their resources,

01:18:07.300 --> 01:18:09.660
[Amit Varma]: would you be able to engineer a harmful virus?

01:18:09.660 --> 01:18:13.540
[Guest]: I'm reading a few papers. And if I have a BCL4 facility, yeah.

01:18:13.540 --> 01:18:14.540
[Guest]: You would.

01:18:14.540 --> 01:18:17.900
[Guest]: Well, there are only two BCL4 facilities in India, so...

01:18:17.900 --> 01:18:23.420
[Amit Varma]: Sure, but like technology, you know, those will eventually, they'll be more common and,

01:18:23.420 --> 01:18:24.420
[Guest]: you know...

01:18:24.420 --> 01:18:28.420
[Guest]: Now I'm regretting saying yeah. Maybe I shouldn't have said yeah. Okay.

01:18:28.420 --> 01:18:32.500
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, it'll be interesting if someone does approach you, let me know, but kindly

01:18:32.500 --> 01:18:33.500
[Amit Varma]: don't accept because...

01:18:33.500 --> 01:18:38.660
[Guest]: No, obviously, I have no intention of doing that. But what I think what we're trying to

01:18:38.660 --> 01:18:45.060
[Guest]: say is that it is feasible to be done. There are a lot more people now who can do it than

01:18:45.060 --> 01:18:51.500
[Guest]: they were 50 years ago, who can actually maybe have put together bits and pieces to create

01:18:51.500 --> 01:18:55.900
[Guest]: a sort of crude weapon. The other thing about biological weapons is that unlike a nuclear

01:18:55.900 --> 01:19:01.180
[Guest]: weapon, it doesn't have to be precise. It can literally be very crude. And the other

01:19:01.180 --> 01:19:07.940
[Guest]: thing I think which we often forget in this entire talk about weapons is that nations

01:19:07.940 --> 01:19:15.220
[Guest]: have, I feel, moved on from the traditional geopolitical warfare to more economic warfare.

01:19:15.220 --> 01:19:19.460
[Guest]: And in economic warfare, biological weapons are much more useful than a nuclear weapon

01:19:19.460 --> 01:19:20.460
[Amit Varma]: is.

01:19:20.460 --> 01:19:21.460
[Amit Varma]: Explain that to me.

01:19:21.460 --> 01:19:24.700
[Guest]: Look at Wuhan now, right. I'm not saying it's a biological weapons attack, but just the

01:19:24.700 --> 01:19:28.820
[Guest]: impact it is going to have on China's economy, the impact it will have on China's morale

01:19:28.820 --> 01:19:36.260
[Guest]: because of them losing a lot of the celebrations of their Lunar New Year. The anxiety that

01:19:36.260 --> 01:19:41.580
[Guest]: is coming to whether she is a good leader or not, whether he has been able to handle

01:19:41.580 --> 01:19:46.460
[Guest]: things well or not, right. And this is in all likelihood a natural outbreak, but just

01:19:46.460 --> 01:19:51.780
[Guest]: the amount of suspicion it has brought in, you can realize the amount of impact it's

01:19:51.780 --> 01:19:58.700
[Guest]: going to have. And so economic warfare, using something like this to destroy somebody's

01:19:58.700 --> 01:20:02.980
[Guest]: food crops, for example, makes more sense than trying to nuke them.

01:20:02.980 --> 01:20:07.220
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, absolutely. And there's nothing you can do about it. The genie is out of the

01:20:07.220 --> 01:20:08.220
[Amit Varma]: bottle in a sense.

01:20:08.220 --> 01:20:15.100
[Guest]: And you cannot tell, even with Wuhan, right. The assumption is that it is a natural outbreak.

01:20:15.100 --> 01:20:18.820
[Guest]: It is very likely going to be a natural outbreak. I mean, there was this entire thing about

01:20:18.820 --> 01:20:24.620
[Guest]: anthrax leaking out from the facility in Russia. But apart from that, we do not seem to have

01:20:24.620 --> 01:20:30.700
[Guest]: a lot of virus outbreaks that have happened as a result of virus escaping labs. But yeah,

01:20:30.700 --> 01:20:34.980
[Guest]: you cannot tell where it has come from. It is very difficult to trace it back. If it

01:20:34.980 --> 01:20:38.620
[Guest]: is a deliberate attack, you cannot even tell which country has done it.

01:20:38.620 --> 01:20:42.700
[Amit Varma]: So let's let's since we can't do anything about this, we must be very dark. Yeah, we

01:20:42.700 --> 01:20:48.220
[Amit Varma]: must instantly become in denial of the possibility of such a thing and instead turn back to subjects

01:20:48.220 --> 01:20:51.460
[Amit Varma]: we can both talk about, which are science and economics, respectively, and talk about

01:20:51.460 --> 01:20:56.780
[Amit Varma]: unintended consequences, like one of the famous textbook cases, which everyone talks about,

01:20:56.780 --> 01:21:00.740
[Amit Varma]: and I believe has been tried in India is, can you genetically modify mosquitoes so they

01:21:00.740 --> 01:21:04.700
[Amit Varma]: don't spread malaria? That is one instance. And another instance, can you genetically

01:21:04.700 --> 01:21:09.900
[Amit Varma]: modify mosquitoes so they stop breeding? And therefore, there are no baby mosquitoes. Yeah.

01:21:09.900 --> 01:21:15.740
[Amit Varma]: Which is your favorite scenario? My favorite scenario is the first because, you know, I

01:21:15.740 --> 01:21:19.100
[Amit Varma]: the spoiler has happened. I know what can happen with the second one, which is basically

01:21:19.100 --> 01:21:23.900
[Amit Varma]: if mosquitoes die out, what will bats eat and the whole ecosystem goes haywire. And

01:21:23.900 --> 01:21:29.580
[Amit Varma]: that is incredibly scary to me. On the other hand, genetically modifying mosquitoes, assuming

01:21:29.580 --> 01:21:33.820
[Amit Varma]: the scientists are fairly confident and it becomes a probabilistic game that there won't

01:21:33.820 --> 01:21:38.580
[Amit Varma]: be other that they can control for other things going wrong. Sounds like a good idea to me.

01:21:38.580 --> 01:21:44.860
[Guest]: What do you think? Tell me enlightened. So I first came across this whole genetically

01:21:44.860 --> 01:21:49.100
[Guest]: modified mosquitoes when Oxitec was doing its studies in Brazil. So Oxitec is a British

01:21:49.100 --> 01:21:55.780
[Guest]: company, which has pioneered this technology. Their technology is your scenario B, where

01:21:55.780 --> 01:22:00.340
[Guest]: you kill off the mosquitoes completely. And they have done this in the Cayman Islands.

01:22:00.340 --> 01:22:05.500
[Guest]: They have done this in Brazil, and they have an ongoing experiment in Maharashtra, in Jalna.

01:22:05.500 --> 01:22:10.980
[Guest]: It has been going on for I think a year and a half now. But I don't know what the results.

01:22:10.980 --> 01:22:14.780
[Amit Varma]: I don't know, don't even know if the results have been made public yet. But how does it

01:22:14.780 --> 01:22:18.220
[Amit Varma]: work? They catch one mosquito and modify it and hope that it... No, no, no. So they make

01:22:18.220 --> 01:22:23.300
[Guest]: the mosquitoes in the lab, and they make it so that these are only male mosquitoes, so

01:22:23.300 --> 01:22:27.220
[Guest]: they won't go out and bite. So only the female mosquitoes will bite you. Yeah, the female

01:22:27.220 --> 01:22:31.980
[Guest]: anaphylis mosquito basically spreads. So the female mosquito bites you because poor thing

01:22:31.980 --> 01:22:37.820
[Guest]: needs your blood to give birth to baby. Okay, so she's not even selfish. Again, she's trying

01:22:37.820 --> 01:22:43.580
[Guest]: to perpetuate because it is natural instinct. So they breed the male mosquitoes in the lab

01:22:43.580 --> 01:22:48.300
[Guest]: and the male mosquitoes have a mutation. So such that when they mate with the wild type

01:22:48.300 --> 01:22:54.300
[Guest]: being the non-mutated female, the offspring doesn't survive. So the offspring dies. And

01:22:54.300 --> 01:22:59.900
[Guest]: that way, you don't get furthering of the population. And the idea is that once the

01:22:59.900 --> 01:23:05.740
[Guest]: male mosquitoes die, you replace them every year with newer and newer mutated male mosquitoes.

01:23:05.740 --> 01:23:12.260
[Guest]: So that is that model. The other model is in which you mutate the mosquito such that

01:23:12.260 --> 01:23:17.300
[Guest]: any larva that comes out, any baby mosquito that comes out cannot harbour the pathogen

01:23:17.300 --> 01:23:21.020
[Guest]: itself. So obviously, the mosquito is not causing dengue or malaria, it is the malarial

01:23:21.020 --> 01:23:25.300
[Guest]: plasmodium or the dengue virus, which once it goes inside you causes the disease. The

01:23:25.300 --> 01:23:30.660
[Guest]: other way is that you change the mosquito so that whenever the malaria plasmodium enters

01:23:30.660 --> 01:23:34.540
[Guest]: a mosquito, it dies within the mosquito itself. So even if the mosquito bites you, there is

01:23:34.540 --> 01:23:38.940
[Guest]: no plasmodium being transferred, so you're not going to suffer the disease. As you said,

01:23:38.940 --> 01:23:43.500
[Guest]: this is a preferred scenario over killing of all mosquitoes because we really cannot

01:23:43.500 --> 01:23:48.100
[Guest]: estimate the impacts that will have on the food chain. There are some people who argue

01:23:48.100 --> 01:23:53.180
[Guest]: that mosquitoes form only a tiny part of the bat's diet, so it might not actually impact

01:23:53.180 --> 01:23:57.460
[Guest]: the bat at all. But it's really difficult to tell. My other argument also is that if

01:23:57.460 --> 01:24:01.380
[Guest]: you completely remove, say, the anopheles mosquito, you might see a rise in some of

01:24:01.380 --> 01:24:06.780
[Guest]: the other mosquito variants in your area, which might not also be desirable. When it

01:24:06.780 --> 01:24:12.940
[Guest]: comes to the other scenario where the mosquito cannot harbour the plasmodium anymore, that

01:24:12.940 --> 01:24:17.100
[Guest]: sounds great. But again, we don't know how it will impact other mosquitoes. They did

01:24:17.100 --> 01:24:22.300
[Guest]: an experiment again in Brazil, where they took mosquitoes from two or three different

01:24:22.300 --> 01:24:28.500
[Guest]: countries and created this mesh mosquito, hybrid mosquito, and released it into confined

01:24:28.500 --> 01:24:34.180
[Guest]: field trials. And what they found was that some of the other mosquitoes also ended up

01:24:34.180 --> 01:24:40.060
[Guest]: getting pieces of DNA, which were not found in Brazil. So, somehow some gene transfer

01:24:40.060 --> 01:24:46.260
[Guest]: has happened. And then this was again a trial which is done by Oxitec. And Oxitec said that

01:24:46.260 --> 01:24:55.700
[Guest]: we did estimate that some level of this kind of gene transfer will happen. Now, suppose

01:24:55.700 --> 01:25:00.980
[Guest]: the mutation itself gets transferred to other species, what issues might that cause? We

01:25:00.980 --> 01:25:07.060
[Guest]: don't know. How effective this whole thing might be in replacing the entire mosquito

01:25:07.060 --> 01:25:13.220
[Guest]: population so that your complete malaria incidence goes down, we don't know. The problem with

01:25:13.220 --> 01:25:17.220
[Guest]: India is that we don't even know where our malaria incidence is. We first have to figure

01:25:17.220 --> 01:25:22.740
[Guest]: out what the hotspots of mosquito bleeding are to be able to then go and do something

01:25:22.740 --> 01:25:27.220
[Guest]: there. We need to have adequate monitoring mechanisms to make sure that if anything does

01:25:27.220 --> 01:25:31.740
[Guest]: go wrong after we release these mosquitoes, we can figure out in time to stop. The only

01:25:31.740 --> 01:25:35.740
[Guest]: difference between a genetically modified plant and a genetically modified mosquito

01:25:35.740 --> 01:25:40.300
[Guest]: is that we cannot recall the mosquito. Once it's released, it's released, it's gone. There

01:25:40.300 --> 01:25:44.860
[Guest]: is no way we can call it back. At least with plants, we can know which pharma has brought

01:25:44.860 --> 01:25:50.260
[Guest]: the seed and we can do something about it. So, I have my own doubts about the technology,

01:25:50.260 --> 01:25:54.900
[Guest]: about how effective it would be, how long it will take for nature to fight back and

01:25:54.900 --> 01:25:59.300
[Guest]: say that, no, no, no, we understand what you're doing. How long till the larva decides that

01:25:59.300 --> 01:26:04.380
[Guest]: we are, sorry, the malaria plasmodium decides to find another host. Whether we have the

01:26:04.380 --> 01:26:09.940
[Guest]: monitoring mechanisms to actually take control of the situation. And my biggest doubt is

01:26:09.940 --> 01:26:14.820
[Guest]: whether we will again use this as a nice way to say that, okay, we don't need to do fumigation,

01:26:14.820 --> 01:26:20.380
[Guest]: we don't need to stay clean, maintain clean household because, hey, we have got any mosquitoes.

01:26:20.380 --> 01:26:25.780
[Guest]: So, Sri Lanka, which is a tiny neighbour for us, managed to become malaria free after five

01:26:25.780 --> 01:26:30.940
[Guest]: years of intensive effort. Uzbekistan became malaria free after intensive efforts, neither

01:26:30.940 --> 01:26:37.580
[Guest]: of them used genetically modified mosquitoes. Whether we have given these other measures

01:26:37.580 --> 01:26:43.780
[Guest]: enough time and enough effort to see if they are effective or not, I don't know. And whether

01:26:43.780 --> 01:26:50.020
[Guest]: we can actually use those existing methods in a better way than trialling out something

01:26:50.020 --> 01:26:55.700
[Guest]: that might risk our ecosystem is something that we have to figure out. I mean, it could

01:26:55.700 --> 01:27:03.060
[Guest]: be a great tool if there were no caveats attached to it. But I do not want it to be used as

01:27:03.060 --> 01:27:07.700
[Guest]: this great solution. It's a great to buy over everything and say that, okay, we don't need

01:27:07.700 --> 01:27:10.140
[Guest]: to do anything now. We just have genetically edited mosquitoes.

01:27:10.140 --> 01:27:13.660
[Amit Varma]: So, at the end of the episode, I really liked with Vijay Kelkar and Ajay Shah, who have

01:27:13.660 --> 01:27:18.860
[Amit Varma]: written that great book, In Service of the Republic. And one of the, like they were talking

01:27:18.860 --> 01:27:24.580
[Amit Varma]: about some of the characteristics of good public policy, and two of them seem to me

01:27:24.580 --> 01:27:29.460
[Amit Varma]: applicable in this instance. One of them is that whatever interventions you make, make

01:27:29.460 --> 01:27:33.900
[Amit Varma]: them on the smallest scale possible, so that you can control, you can measure, you can

01:27:33.900 --> 01:27:39.300
[Amit Varma]: roll back. And the second one is that it should be reversible, so that if something goes wrong,

01:27:39.300 --> 01:27:43.540
[Amit Varma]: you can turn track. And it seems to me that in the case of this whole mosquito thing,

01:27:43.540 --> 01:27:48.120
[Amit Varma]: one the scale is actually very large, because once they are out in the wild, the consequences

01:27:48.120 --> 01:27:52.860
[Amit Varma]: can be across the globe and forever. So, it's not a small scale at all. And two, it's not

01:27:52.860 --> 01:27:58.380
[Guest]: reversible. Ideally, a lot of these gene editing experiments at the population level have been

01:27:58.380 --> 01:28:03.460
[Guest]: done on islands. I have no idea why they picked Jalna. I mean, Jalna seems like a poor choice

01:28:03.460 --> 01:28:07.500
[Guest]: to have. You could have ideally picked an island where you could do this kind of a study

01:28:07.500 --> 01:28:12.980
[Amit Varma]: and try to look at the impact on the ecosystem. Yeah. And you know, here, what do you think

01:28:12.980 --> 01:28:18.660
[Amit Varma]: of like the common argument used against genetic modification, and especially being used and

01:28:18.660 --> 01:28:24.660
[Amit Varma]: I think in that context, it's a bad argument against GMOs is a precautionary principle,

01:28:24.660 --> 01:28:29.000
[Amit Varma]: right? Because we don't know what may happen, let's not do it. And my fundamental opposition

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:32.260
[Amit Varma]: to the precautionary principle, of course, is that no progress would ever happen if we

01:28:32.260 --> 01:28:37.100
[Amit Varma]: followed the precautionary principle. And in the case of GMO, the politics behind it

01:28:37.100 --> 01:28:42.100
[Amit Varma]: absolutely disgusts me because the science is pretty unanimous on, you know, GMOs being

01:28:42.100 --> 01:28:46.940
[Amit Varma]: completely safe, and they've saved millions of life. And for, you know, since the 90s,

01:28:46.940 --> 01:28:51.020
[Amit Varma]: when they became common across the Western world for millions and millions of hectares,

01:28:51.020 --> 01:28:55.540
[Amit Varma]: there have been absolutely no side effects. And the benefits to nutrition and all of that

01:28:55.540 --> 01:28:58.780
[Amit Varma]: have been remarkable. I wrote a column on this, which I'll link from the show notes

01:28:58.780 --> 01:29:05.740
[Amit Varma]: about the different satyagrahas in India where farmers have fought for their rights against

01:29:05.740 --> 01:29:10.820
[Amit Varma]: politically motivated NGOs. But in general, in GMOs, I know we'll both agree on this,

01:29:10.820 --> 01:29:17.060
[Amit Varma]: but in general, when the precautionary principle is sort of invoked, what's your sense on that?

01:29:17.060 --> 01:29:20.660
[Amit Varma]: Like, where do you draw a line and say that it's applicable here? And where do you say,

01:29:20.660 --> 01:29:24.060
[Guest]: okay, it's not? I think for me, it is applicable when it allows

01:29:24.060 --> 01:29:30.020
[Guest]: for consent, right? So, for a GMO crop, for example, if I do not subscribe to the idea

01:29:30.020 --> 01:29:34.620
[Guest]: that GMOs are healthy, I can say that I don't want to buy this product because it says it's

01:29:34.620 --> 01:29:40.220
[Guest]: a GMO product, right? If you tomorrow decide that you're going to release GM mosquitoes

01:29:40.220 --> 01:29:45.620
[Guest]: in my environment, I really have no other choice apart from moving. I have no idea how

01:29:45.620 --> 01:29:51.820
[Guest]: you'll take my consent into account when releasing mosquitoes. So, for me, everything comes down

01:29:51.820 --> 01:29:58.300
[Guest]: to the idea of whether individual consent is enabled in a situation or not. And I think

01:29:58.300 --> 01:30:03.900
[Guest]: for GMOs, for the crops, it's the same. Farmers have the right to choose whether they want

01:30:03.900 --> 01:30:08.740
[Guest]: to use GM crops or not, and consumers have the right to choose whether they want to eat

01:30:08.740 --> 01:30:12.740
[Guest]: GM crops or not. And then you can let the market decide what happens.

01:30:12.740 --> 01:30:20.420
[Amit Varma]: That's tremendous clarity, which is a good time to segue into the policy questions. Speaking

01:30:20.420 --> 01:30:26.940
[Amit Varma]: to you now and before, you've got a lot of clarity on how and why we should frame policy

01:30:26.940 --> 01:30:30.740
[Amit Varma]: and how we should look at these issues, partly because you are both someone trained in the

01:30:30.740 --> 01:30:34.660
[Amit Varma]: science and passionate about it, and you're also kind of trained in public policy. But

01:30:34.660 --> 01:30:39.140
[Amit Varma]: what's been your experience of working in the policy ecosystem of this in India, which

01:30:39.140 --> 01:30:43.700
[Amit Varma]: I assume must be young and growing and learning? And tell me a bit about it.

01:30:43.700 --> 01:30:49.700
[Guest]: It actually seems to be old and unlearning. A lot of the policy makers I've met have extremely

01:30:49.700 --> 01:30:56.500
[Guest]: rigid views about what should be done. There is this subservience to what comes from outside

01:30:56.500 --> 01:31:05.180
[Guest]: India and extremely risk covers, right. We do not look at any incoming technology proactively.

01:31:05.180 --> 01:31:12.580
[Guest]: We do not want, we do not take those decisions which might end up, how do I say this, upsetting

01:31:12.580 --> 01:31:18.820
[Guest]: certain sections of the society. So, I don't think we leverage the strong points that we

01:31:18.820 --> 01:31:24.180
[Guest]: have. A, we have got, well, not a lot, but we've got a bunch of really good scientists.

01:31:24.180 --> 01:31:30.620
[Guest]: We have got good infrastructure, and we have got a huge population riddled with problems

01:31:30.620 --> 01:31:35.300
[Guest]: that basically provides ample opportunities for you to try and do something about it.

01:31:35.300 --> 01:31:39.420
[Guest]: When I was in the UK, when I was doing my PhD on breast cancer, I was working with breast

01:31:39.420 --> 01:31:47.060
[Guest]: cancer patients. And in four years, I got to see 16 patients. That's it. And one of

01:31:47.060 --> 01:31:51.180
[Guest]: the reasons why I wanted to return to India was I thought that if I wanted to work on

01:31:51.180 --> 01:31:58.140
[Guest]: cancer, I need to see patients. And I'm going to get to see those patients in India, right.

01:31:58.140 --> 01:32:06.740
[Guest]: But here, we don't seem to appreciate the fact that we have that opportunity to be able

01:32:06.740 --> 01:32:12.620
[Guest]: to change so many lives. There's a fear that because there are a lot of vulnerable people,

01:32:12.620 --> 01:32:18.460
[Guest]: foreign companies might come in and exploit them. But I mean, that is your role as a policymaker

01:32:18.460 --> 01:32:23.660
[Guest]: to be able to protect your people, but also not shield them away from opportunities to

01:32:23.660 --> 01:32:31.260
[Guest]: a better life. So yeah, it is. It is surprising because this whole thing about heritable gene

01:32:31.260 --> 01:32:35.420
[Guest]: editing and the ethical causes behind it. I've had a number of conversations where I've

01:32:35.420 --> 01:32:39.460
[Guest]: asked people, do you think it's unethical? They will say yes, it is unethical. Then I

01:32:39.460 --> 01:32:43.420
[Guest]: asked them, why do you think it is unethical? And they say, oh, because the science is not

01:32:43.420 --> 01:32:48.660
[Guest]: up to date, it is premature. And then I go, but that's a scientific risk. It's not an

01:32:48.660 --> 01:32:53.740
[Guest]: ethical risk. So in their minds themselves, they have not understood the difference between

01:32:53.740 --> 01:32:58.900
[Guest]: what is ethically correct and what is scientifically correct. And then when you talk about ethics,

01:32:58.900 --> 01:33:04.140
[Guest]: which is very deeply rooted in religion and faith, that you have to make people make the

01:33:04.140 --> 01:33:09.780
[Guest]: choice. Again, in the US, there seems to be scientific consensus that germline gene editing

01:33:09.780 --> 01:33:16.140
[Guest]: is unethical. But when the Pew Research Group did a civilian study, they found that 87%

01:33:16.140 --> 01:33:24.860
[Guest]: people, US civilians, thought that using germline gene editing in babies to correct a debilitating

01:33:24.860 --> 01:33:31.260
[Guest]: disease or a life threatening disease is acceptable. So we don't even know where our concepts of

01:33:31.260 --> 01:33:32.260
[Guest]: ethics are coming from.

01:33:32.260 --> 01:33:36.220
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's interesting and a lot of it may be an instinctive ickiness. Like for example,

01:33:36.220 --> 01:33:42.420
[Amit Varma]: when Louise Brown, the first rest of your baby was born, her parents, Leslie and John

01:33:42.420 --> 01:33:46.820
[Amit Varma]: got trolled viciously, as you would be in those days before social media with a lot

01:33:46.820 --> 01:33:51.740
[Amit Varma]: of hate mail, including parcels containing plastic fetuses, which had been splattered

01:33:51.740 --> 01:33:58.420
[Amit Varma]: with blood. And you kind of wondered at what kind of anger causes someone to sort of do

01:33:58.420 --> 01:34:03.780
[Amit Varma]: that and where these sort of, it almost seems as if some premium taboo has been breached.

01:34:03.780 --> 01:34:08.100
[Guest]: Yeah, it just happens with every new technology, right? When the recombinant DNA first came

01:34:08.100 --> 01:34:13.460
[Guest]: in, so recombinant DNA is basically you can change your DNA, you can create a DNA inside

01:34:13.460 --> 01:34:19.540
[Guest]: a lab, and any change DNA fault, that's what is known as recombinant DNA. And when we understood

01:34:19.540 --> 01:34:26.060
[Guest]: that we could, say, take a human gene and express it in a bacterial cell to create a

01:34:26.060 --> 01:34:30.180
[Guest]: human protein, and then we could use that human protein back in humans, people were

01:34:30.180 --> 01:34:35.500
[Guest]: scared about what would happen, right? What would people be doing with such kind of technology?

01:34:35.500 --> 01:34:40.060
[Guest]: And there was a ban on recombinant DNA for many years. And then there was this entire

01:34:40.060 --> 01:34:47.260
[Guest]: episode of when HIV first came into America. And it quickly spread among hemophiliacs.

01:34:47.260 --> 01:34:52.940
[Guest]: So hemophilia is obviously this disease that means your blood doesn't clot. So if you have

01:34:52.940 --> 01:34:58.220
[Guest]: a tiny cut, you might actually bleed yourself out. It's very common among the European monarchy,

01:34:58.220 --> 01:35:02.860
[Guest]: for example. That's something I will come back to later. But so hemophilia, if you're

01:35:02.860 --> 01:35:08.420
[Guest]: hemophilia, you require a lot of blood transfusions. And because AIDS had made, HIV had made its

01:35:08.420 --> 01:35:13.620
[Guest]: way to the US, and people did not really know where it had come from or how it spread, a

01:35:13.620 --> 01:35:19.260
[Guest]: lot of tainted blood actually went into hemophiliacs without the knowledge that it had HIV. And

01:35:19.260 --> 01:35:23.740
[Guest]: then it became like a hemophiliac disease. And people really were scared, because as

01:35:23.740 --> 01:35:28.260
[Guest]: a hemophiliac, you really had no other choice than undergoing a blood transfusion. But you

01:35:28.260 --> 01:35:31.820
[Guest]: do not know whether you'll end up with HIV or not. And that is when recombinant DNA came

01:35:31.820 --> 01:35:36.380
[Guest]: to rescue because people had been creating the protein that was missing in hemophilia

01:35:36.380 --> 01:35:42.260
[Guest]: using recombinant DNA in labs. This was not tainted blood. This was the pure protein.

01:35:42.260 --> 01:35:46.980
[Guest]: It could be given without any worry of spreading HIV. And then the recombinant DNA just burst

01:35:46.980 --> 01:35:51.380
[Guest]: on the scene. People were more agreeable to it, more acceptable of the technology. But

01:35:51.380 --> 01:35:58.620
[Guest]: it came at the cost of many lives. And I think it might become very similar with gene editing.

01:35:58.620 --> 01:36:02.820
[Guest]: Question really is, can we just learn from what happened in the 1980s and 90s? And say

01:36:02.820 --> 01:36:05.540
[Guest]: that, okay, we don't want to pay that cost of life anymore.

01:36:05.540 --> 01:36:09.260
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me just looking at incentives, the incentive of a bureaucrat who's making

01:36:09.260 --> 01:36:14.380
[Amit Varma]: a policy decision about this would be if he is if he doesn't understand this new technology,

01:36:14.380 --> 01:36:18.740
[Amit Varma]: like say, in the case of recombinant DNA, and he says that, okay, I don't really understand

01:36:18.740 --> 01:36:23.420
[Amit Varma]: this, why should I take a risk? Doing nothing and banning it is the safest way for me because

01:36:23.420 --> 01:36:29.180
[Amit Varma]: if I allow it and something goes wrong, and would this and this is a very natural, rational

01:36:29.180 --> 01:36:33.740
[Amit Varma]: way for the bureaucrat in question to behave. But would it then point to a structural problem

01:36:33.740 --> 01:36:39.820
[Amit Varma]: in the system that there aren't enough scientists or people with scientific knowledge embedded

01:36:39.820 --> 01:36:45.260
[Amit Varma]: in the policymaking mechanism, so that such fears don't arise and such decisions can be

01:36:45.260 --> 01:36:48.780
[Amit Varma]: taken with much more in much more informed ways?

01:36:48.780 --> 01:36:52.300
[Guest]: Yeah, and with transparent data, I think one of the things that we have really struggled

01:36:52.300 --> 01:36:57.780
[Guest]: with is getting data and being able to communicate that data in a coherent manner. We saw this

01:36:57.780 --> 01:37:02.500
[Guest]: happen with GMOs, we saw it happen with BT Cotton, we saw a lot of narrative being asserted

01:37:02.500 --> 01:37:08.460
[Guest]: by anti GMO lobbies simply because the government of India never released data on how good the

01:37:08.460 --> 01:37:15.020
[Guest]: crops were. We saw this happen with GM Mustard and GM Brinjal, which passed safety tests

01:37:15.020 --> 01:37:18.980
[Guest]: by the government of India, but were never approved by the government of India. They

01:37:18.980 --> 01:37:19.980
[Amit Varma]: were approved in Bangladesh.

01:37:19.980 --> 01:37:23.620
[Guest]: And they benefited Bangladesh enormously. And our poor farmers suffered.

01:37:23.620 --> 01:37:29.220
[Guest]: Yeah, but release the data we need to see, right? I mean, one of the other issues is

01:37:29.220 --> 01:37:36.220
[Guest]: that we have been unable to accept limitations. If something doesn't work, it doesn't work.

01:37:36.220 --> 01:37:39.500
[Guest]: It's okay to say that it doesn't work and try to figure out an answer. But we simply

01:37:39.500 --> 01:37:48.260
[Guest]: won't do that. With BT Cotton, I thought that it should be anticipated that the ballworm

01:37:48.260 --> 01:37:53.900
[Guest]: against which BT Cotton provides resistance will develop resistance because hey, nature

01:37:53.900 --> 01:37:58.500
[Guest]: finds a way, right? It will happen. We have seen it happen again and again and again,

01:37:58.500 --> 01:38:03.220
[Guest]: nothing's going to change now. So, it will happen. And to be able to anticipate that,

01:38:03.220 --> 01:38:07.820
[Guest]: to be able to work with farmers so that they don't suffer a loss is something that is completely

01:38:07.820 --> 01:38:14.060
[Guest]: undoable. But when technology comes and we either look at it as this miraculous cure

01:38:14.060 --> 01:38:20.060
[Guest]: that is going to be a one-stop solution that we never have to look at it again, is hurting

01:38:20.060 --> 01:38:24.020
[Guest]: us. Either we look at it from that way, or we look at it from the way that no, no, this

01:38:24.020 --> 01:38:28.940
[Guest]: is going to be a complete disaster. So, we shouldn't do it, right?

01:38:28.940 --> 01:38:35.980
[Guest]: And particularly for the GMOs, I've heard both the narratives. And they're so extremely

01:38:35.980 --> 01:38:42.460
[Guest]: deeming of the other one. They are so extremely, they're just not agreeable to hearing each

01:38:42.460 --> 01:38:49.140
[Guest]: other out. They are not agreeing to the fact that both of them have some merits, right?

01:38:49.140 --> 01:38:53.460
[Guest]: There are some risks. We are not going to say that everything is great. At the same

01:38:53.460 --> 01:38:58.620
[Guest]: time, we cannot say that nothing is worth it. But just getting them to the middle ground

01:38:58.620 --> 01:39:01.860
[Amit Varma]: is very difficult. Exactly. And in the case of GMOs, for three

01:39:01.860 --> 01:39:06.300
[Amit Varma]: decades, there were absolutely no side effects anywhere. The rest of the world adopted it.

01:39:06.300 --> 01:39:13.020
[Guest]: And we were making our... I was at the BRICS academic forum last year,

01:39:13.020 --> 01:39:18.540
[Guest]: on a panel on how the BRICS nations can cooperate on agriculture. And someone from the South

01:39:18.540 --> 01:39:24.900
[Guest]: African contingent stood up and asked, but GMOs are hazardous to health. So, I don't

01:39:24.900 --> 01:39:29.180
[Guest]: want them to come into South Africa. And I was thinking, okay, these people are probably

01:39:29.180 --> 01:39:35.820
[Guest]: the best that South Africa can send to academic forum. So, obviously must have an academic

01:39:35.820 --> 01:39:41.740
[Guest]: pedigree, must be extremely well educated, has come with scientific people from his community

01:39:41.740 --> 01:39:48.420
[Guest]: and yet believes that GMOs are bad for health. So, yeah, there's something wrong with the

01:39:48.420 --> 01:39:51.620
[Guest]: narrative shaping that we seem to have lost out on.

01:39:51.620 --> 01:39:56.060
[Amit Varma]: So how can this policymaking process in India be reformed? Like, for example, could you

01:39:56.060 --> 01:40:00.980
[Amit Varma]: illustrate with the example of any specific policy decision? And what are the different

01:40:00.980 --> 01:40:05.820
[Amit Varma]: sort of pulls and pressures that go in? What are the considerations? And, you know...

01:40:05.820 --> 01:40:12.820
[Guest]: So, for the gene editing policy, the policy actually just came out in December 2019. The

01:40:12.820 --> 01:40:21.500
[Guest]: first meeting was held under pressure in 2017. I was not part of any meetings, I just know

01:40:21.500 --> 01:40:27.220
[Guest]: about this from outside. So, in 2017, they held the first meeting. This was the ICMR

01:40:27.220 --> 01:40:32.380
[Guest]: and DBT, which is the Indian Council for Medical Research and the Department of Biotechnology.

01:40:32.380 --> 01:40:38.900
[Guest]: And then nothing moved for two years until the babies in China were born, the genetically

01:40:38.900 --> 01:40:43.860
[Guest]: modified babies, which again put on a lot of international pressure on countries to

01:40:43.860 --> 01:40:45.180
[Guest]: pass some sort of policy.

01:40:45.180 --> 01:40:49.220
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that, what genetically modified babies in China?

01:40:49.220 --> 01:40:55.700
[Guest]: So, this Chinese scientist was working on HIV for a long time. And there is a particular

01:40:55.700 --> 01:41:01.900
[Guest]: receptor in the immune cells where the HIV virus binds and goes in. So, if you remove

01:41:01.900 --> 01:41:08.980
[Guest]: the receptor, the CCR5 receptor, you basically can afford immunity to HIV. So, he was working

01:41:08.980 --> 01:41:16.940
[Guest]: with couples in Africa, where HIV is pretty common. And he decided to find couples where

01:41:16.940 --> 01:41:24.700
[Guest]: the father had HIV positive, the mother did not. So, take the egg and the sperm, create

01:41:24.700 --> 01:41:31.060
[Guest]: an embryo and modify the embryo such that it removes a part of this receptor. And then

01:41:31.060 --> 01:41:37.620
[Guest]: ideally, the child should not get the HIV, which her father has. So, he created this

01:41:37.620 --> 01:41:50.500
[Guest]: twins Nana and Lulu. And they were born in November 2018. And he made this landmark announcement.

01:41:50.500 --> 01:41:56.980
[Guest]: And the world shook. Because then everyone was saying that no, no, germline genetic is

01:41:56.980 --> 01:42:00.300
[Guest]: something we will never get into, we should not get into. There were a lot of sceptics

01:42:00.300 --> 01:42:03.340
[Guest]: who said that someone or the others is going to do it. So, we do not see the point of a

01:42:03.340 --> 01:42:08.180
[Guest]: moratorium. But there was this supposed self-imposed moratorium.

01:42:08.180 --> 01:42:09.860
[Amit Varma]: And then Nana and Lulu come along.

01:42:09.860 --> 01:42:15.220
[Guest]: And then these two kids come along. And obviously, then the Chinese Academy of Sciences decided

01:42:15.220 --> 01:42:19.900
[Guest]: to take swift action. They put him under house arrest. He is jailed now for three years.

01:42:19.900 --> 01:42:24.740
[Guest]: We still do not know what has happened with the kids. They were taken under state control.

01:42:24.740 --> 01:42:31.380
[Guest]: But it is China. So, everything is under state control, I guess. And there have been some

01:42:31.380 --> 01:42:34.660
[Guest]: studies which some would say that the babies are fine. Some would say that the babies might

01:42:34.660 --> 01:42:39.140
[Guest]: not live long. But we really do not know what is happening there.

01:42:39.140 --> 01:42:42.420
[Guest]: After that, there was a guy in Russia who said, I want to do the same experiment, but

01:42:42.420 --> 01:42:48.300
[Guest]: that the Chinese scientist's science was wrong. So, there were some arguments that the experiment

01:42:48.300 --> 01:42:51.260
[Guest]: that he did was scientifically incorrect. I mean, forget the ethics part, but scientifically

01:42:51.260 --> 01:42:54.300
[Guest]: could have done better. So, this Russian guy came and said, no, no, I will do the same

01:42:54.300 --> 01:42:57.980
[Guest]: experiment, but I will do it scientifically better. But then the Russian government said

01:42:57.980 --> 01:43:00.780
[Guest]: no doing. So, that fizzled out.

01:43:00.780 --> 01:43:05.700
[Amit Varma]: So, you're coming back to the question of, you know, the Indian policy on that. In 2017,

01:43:05.700 --> 01:43:12.220
[Guest]: they met and then this happened in 2018. And how did all of that impact the policy?

01:43:12.220 --> 01:43:17.580
[Guest]: So then they came out with an actual draft policy. The draft policy came out in, I think,

01:43:17.580 --> 01:43:24.020
[Guest]: August last year, that they announced it and they gave four days for public consultation.

01:43:24.020 --> 01:43:27.180
[Guest]: So, it came out on Monday and they said Friday is your last year.

01:43:27.180 --> 01:43:28.180
[Amit Varma]: Good Lord, that's ridiculous.

01:43:28.180 --> 01:43:35.460
[Guest]: And luckily I saw it. So, I gave back my comments, but I've not heard anything back from them.

01:43:35.460 --> 01:43:42.460
[Guest]: And the final draft that was released in December is exactly the same draft as the one for public

01:43:42.460 --> 01:43:45.780
[Guest]: consultation. So, I don't know if they've actually, if actually anyone has commented

01:43:45.780 --> 01:43:50.900
[Guest]: or if they've actually even looked at the comments or not. So, and one of my bigger

01:43:50.900 --> 01:43:56.860
[Guest]: issues about that draft, and I think it summarizes all of our comments so far, is that it says

01:43:56.860 --> 01:44:04.500
[Guest]: that gene therapies are going to be allowed for therapeutic benefits. And I have no idea

01:44:04.500 --> 01:44:06.260
[Guest]: what therapeutic benefits is.

01:44:06.260 --> 01:44:07.260
[Amit Varma]: It can be defined anyway.

01:44:07.260 --> 01:44:13.940
[Guest]: It can be anything. And the problem that such ambiguity in policy brings is that, A, India

01:44:13.940 --> 01:44:19.180
[Guest]: really requires investment in science, research and development. Our government spends very,

01:44:19.180 --> 01:44:25.380
[Guest]: very little on R&D. And no private investor is going to come in when you cannot promise

01:44:25.380 --> 01:44:29.940
[Guest]: that the product you're making is going to be acceptable or not at the end of the day.

01:44:29.940 --> 01:44:36.020
[Guest]: And when you have something called therapeutic benefits in it, I really cannot tell. It's

01:44:36.020 --> 01:44:41.300
[Guest]: then up to whoever is the decision making committee to decide what ambit that falls

01:44:41.300 --> 01:44:42.300
[Amit Varma]: into.

01:44:42.300 --> 01:44:47.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean, then it's again laid open to bureaucratic discretion, they may, you know, err on the

01:44:47.020 --> 01:44:52.060
[Amit Varma]: side of safety and so on and so forth. So, what reforms could be made to it to make them

01:44:52.060 --> 01:44:57.860
[Amit Varma]: more receptive to new science and to knowledge and to better data, as you pointed out earlier?

01:44:57.860 --> 01:45:01.580
[Amit Varma]: You know, how could it work better? Because I'm imagining the pace of change is so fast

01:45:01.580 --> 01:45:05.780
[Amit Varma]: that these are old world bureaucrats in an old world governance system actually designed

01:45:05.780 --> 01:45:10.500
[Amit Varma]: in the 19th century by the British. And there is so much change happening so much information

01:45:10.500 --> 01:45:13.740
[Amit Varma]: coming in. It's an archaic system in this modern world.

01:45:13.740 --> 01:45:19.020
[Guest]: Yeah, it's a copy paste of the old guidelines. So they'll pick some old guidelines and say,

01:45:19.020 --> 01:45:22.260
[Guest]: you know, whatever we can copy paste, you can copy paste and wherever gene editing has

01:45:22.260 --> 01:45:26.220
[Guest]: to be inserted can be inserted. The gene editing guidelines actually are a little more progressive

01:45:26.220 --> 01:45:31.060
[Guest]: than the stem cell guidelines, which came out in 2017 that look at stem cell therapies.

01:45:31.060 --> 01:45:36.700
[Guest]: In that, A, the gene editing guidelines actually say that we will form working groups of scientists

01:45:36.700 --> 01:45:42.180
[Guest]: and patient groups and lawyers for particular diseases, right. This was something that even

01:45:42.180 --> 01:45:46.780
[Guest]: Takashi's working document has argued for the past two years that let's not have one

01:45:46.780 --> 01:45:51.780
[Guest]: committee that determines everything for all diseases. So, that was something that we found

01:45:51.780 --> 01:45:56.820
[Guest]: was very progressive. The other thing that I think they could have done and what we had

01:45:56.820 --> 01:46:01.700
[Guest]: suggested was that have the working group come out with detailed guidelines for the

01:46:01.700 --> 01:46:08.940
[Guest]: disease. Since you are the primary funder for a lot of the research anyways, you can

01:46:08.940 --> 01:46:14.060
[Guest]: actually have the luxury of saying that these are the 10 diseases I want to prioritize research

01:46:14.060 --> 01:46:19.860
[Guest]: on because data shows that they are most common in India. So, you can say that these are the

01:46:19.860 --> 01:46:26.500
[Guest]: 10 diseases, we have these 10 working groups who will say that if your solution can offer

01:46:26.500 --> 01:46:32.100
[Guest]: say 90 percent efficacy, then we will allow it to the next stage, right. If you have that

01:46:32.100 --> 01:46:36.900
[Guest]: kind of clarity built in, then we can actually see people getting more and more into research

01:46:36.900 --> 01:46:42.460
[Guest]: and creating gene editing therapeutics instead of just using it for fundamental research.

01:46:42.460 --> 01:46:48.100
[Guest]: The other thing that we thought was it is still a very bureaucratic system. So, we already

01:46:48.100 --> 01:46:52.700
[Guest]: have a few committees at the institution level. So, say at a research institution, you will

01:46:52.700 --> 01:46:57.260
[Guest]: have an Institutional Biosafety Committee, you will have a Stem Cell Committee, and then

01:46:57.260 --> 01:47:00.820
[Guest]: you will also have a National Apex Committee who has to see what you are doing. So, a lot

01:47:00.820 --> 01:47:05.380
[Guest]: of monitoring going on. This guideline actually forms a third committee on to sit on top of

01:47:05.380 --> 01:47:09.860
[Guest]: all of that. So, we are like why have all of these committees, just create one that

01:47:09.860 --> 01:47:14.420
[Guest]: says that ok, your research is ok or not ok. Streamline the decision-making, reduce the

01:47:14.420 --> 01:47:17.340
[Amit Varma]: lag. Yeah, because now you are just going through like four or five committees to figure

01:47:17.340 --> 01:47:21.340
[Guest]: out whether you can actually do what you want to do, after which you start doing what you

01:47:21.340 --> 01:47:26.140
[Amit Varma]: want to do. And you kind of mentioned guidelines having things like ok, if you have more than

01:47:26.140 --> 01:47:30.940
[Amit Varma]: an X percent chance of happening. And it kind of just struck me that new technologies in

01:47:30.940 --> 01:47:39.140
[Amit Varma]: any field, new technologies have a far higher bar of acceptance than existing technologies.

01:47:39.140 --> 01:47:43.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just to take an example, for example, in the case of technology in cricket, which

01:47:43.580 --> 01:47:48.660
[Amit Varma]: I have, which I argued from from the early 2000s onwards, when I was in cricket for that

01:47:48.660 --> 01:47:54.220
[Amit Varma]: we should embrace technology in cricket. And my only metric was that is the technology

01:47:54.220 --> 01:47:59.060
[Amit Varma]: more reliable than the umpire? Not that it should be perfect, but is it better than what

01:47:59.060 --> 01:48:03.260
[Amit Varma]: is existing? And it's not even a binary because technology is an aid to umpire. So, you're

01:48:03.260 --> 01:48:08.460
[Amit Varma]: comparing umpire alone against umpire with technology. And say if umpires have a 90%

01:48:08.460 --> 01:48:14.020
[Amit Varma]: accuracy rate, I am happy then if umpire plus technology has a 95% accuracy rate. I'm not

01:48:14.020 --> 01:48:20.180
[Amit Varma]: going to use the remaining 5%, you know, to argue against technology and to build an alarmist

01:48:20.180 --> 01:48:24.340
[Amit Varma]: case. And is that something that often happens in the case of new technologies?

01:48:24.340 --> 01:48:30.500
[Guest]: I think it does. I mean, actually, I don't know, because it gets it really gets compared

01:48:30.500 --> 01:48:36.700
[Guest]: with what we have existing, right on and how we can improve whatever is existing. Your

01:48:36.700 --> 01:48:41.460
[Guest]: first mindset to look at new technology is to look at risks. People rarely look at benefits

01:48:41.460 --> 01:48:46.940
[Guest]: first. The most extreme scenario pops in your head first. And then you compare it to the

01:48:46.940 --> 01:48:53.700
[Guest]: most extreme scenario of what your existing technology has. And the problem is that with

01:48:53.700 --> 01:48:58.300
[Guest]: a new technology, you don't know what the risk is. So, your brain automatically starts

01:48:58.300 --> 01:49:01.300
[Guest]: thinking that you're on Battlestar Galactica, right?

01:49:01.300 --> 01:49:04.980
[Amit Varma]: Siberian elephants will suddenly come back to India and destroy everything.

01:49:04.980 --> 01:49:11.300
[Guest]: Yeah. So, that I think is bigger problem is that we have not been able to make a calibrated

01:49:11.300 --> 01:49:15.820
[Guest]: guess of what might actually happen. And for that, you need more scientists in

01:49:15.820 --> 01:49:20.780
[Guest]: the decision making process. But we also need more progressive scientists.

01:49:20.780 --> 01:49:26.620
[Guest]: We need more young scientists in policy roles. We need more young scientists trained in policy

01:49:26.620 --> 01:49:31.300
[Guest]: role. I think one of the other issues that I see with scientists who contribute to policymaking

01:49:31.300 --> 01:49:33.260
[Guest]: is that they're not being trained in public policy.

01:49:33.260 --> 01:49:36.620
[Amit Varma]: So, they don't know how to frame a problem in policy terms.

01:49:36.620 --> 01:49:41.540
[Guest]: Yeah. And they have always been in their nice academic luxury bubble. I might get a lot

01:49:41.540 --> 01:49:48.820
[Guest]: of flack for saying that, but it is true. They have not been exposed outside of their

01:49:48.820 --> 01:49:53.820
[Guest]: campus to see how technology can integrate with and change society and how society can

01:49:53.820 --> 01:50:01.220
[Guest]: actually adopt technology. So, for example, I work with a lot of patient groups, right?

01:50:01.220 --> 01:50:04.500
[Guest]: And when I speak to scientists, they're like, ha, gemline gene editing, makes no sense.

01:50:04.500 --> 01:50:11.540
[Guest]: We don't need it. I'm yet to come across a patient group representative or a family member

01:50:11.540 --> 01:50:16.020
[Guest]: of a patient group who has told me that let's not go down the gene editing because the pain

01:50:16.020 --> 01:50:20.580
[Guest]: is very real for them. I mean, you can put everything aside, but for them to see their

01:50:20.580 --> 01:50:25.260
[Amit Varma]: loved one out of pain is the most important. I mean, if you have kids with Down syndrome

01:50:25.260 --> 01:50:29.540
[Amit Varma]: or you have whatever, any kind of health problem to your near and loved one, you know, why

01:50:29.540 --> 01:50:31.540
[Guest]: should you not make your life better?

01:50:31.540 --> 01:50:39.980
[Guest]: So just to understand the whole thing of benefit to risk ratio, to take out opportunity cost,

01:50:39.980 --> 01:50:43.140
[Guest]: basic concepts of economics, supply and demand is something that scientists are not trained

01:50:43.140 --> 01:50:46.140
[Guest]: with. I mean, they're not supposed to be trained with. But if you're going to make a policy

01:50:46.140 --> 01:50:50.300
[Guest]: decision, then you really need to know these facts, these concepts.

01:50:50.300 --> 01:50:55.220
[Amit Varma]: Fair point. So, you know, before we kind of wind up, a couple of things I'd like you to

01:50:55.220 --> 01:50:59.300
[Amit Varma]: talk about. One is haemophilia in Europe, something that you mentioned about how royals

01:50:59.300 --> 01:51:04.700
[Amit Varma]: apparently had more of it and royal blood and all bled out faster and did not stop bleeding.

01:51:04.700 --> 01:51:07.860
[Amit Varma]: And the other one, and this makes a whole episode non-structured because it's a very

01:51:07.860 --> 01:51:13.460
[Amit Varma]: arbitrary thing and I didn't ask it at the right time. But about, for example, the effect

01:51:13.460 --> 01:51:18.540
[Amit Varma]: that endogamy had on gene lines. For example, I had done an episode with Tony Joseph on

01:51:18.540 --> 01:51:24.340
[Amit Varma]: his wonderful, wonderful book, Early Indians. And he had spoken about how after all the

01:51:24.340 --> 01:51:29.660
[Amit Varma]: different waves of migration, first the out of Africa migration, and then the West Asian

01:51:29.660 --> 01:51:34.260
[Amit Varma]: migration from Harappa and downwards, and then finally the Aryan migration, there was

01:51:34.260 --> 01:51:39.500
[Amit Varma]: a lot of intermingling for a couple of centuries, everyone's having a party, everyone's having

01:51:39.500 --> 01:51:44.740
[Amit Varma]: fun with everyone else. And then suddenly that stops. And it's endogamy. 2000 years

01:51:44.740 --> 01:51:49.380
[Amit Varma]: ago, and it says David Reich describes it, you know, while the Han Chinese are a large

01:51:49.380 --> 01:51:54.340
[Amit Varma]: population, India is actually a collection of many, many small populations, because it's

01:51:54.340 --> 01:51:58.940
[Amit Varma]: endogamy. And, and people are, you know, a lot of it determined by the caste system that

01:51:58.940 --> 01:52:03.740
[Amit Varma]: there simply isn't that much mixing going around. And I won't ask you to elaborate on

01:52:03.740 --> 01:52:10.060
[Amit Varma]: the politics or the sociological aspects of that. But what did it mean in terms of genetics?

01:52:10.060 --> 01:52:11.060
[Guest]: So these two questions.

01:52:11.060 --> 01:52:18.500
[Guest]: Right. So the first one about Monarchian hemophilia. So Queen Victoria actually had, was a carrier

01:52:18.500 --> 01:52:24.260
[Guest]: for the diseased hemophilia gene. Since this is an X linked gene, so women tend not to

01:52:24.260 --> 01:52:29.220
[Guest]: suffer from it so much unless both of their X chromosomes are impacted. But men because

01:52:29.220 --> 01:52:35.420
[Guest]: they only have the X from the mother will show hemophilia. So Queen Victoria actually

01:52:35.420 --> 01:52:40.420
[Guest]: passed it down to her sons and her daughters were carriers. And because back then, you

01:52:40.420 --> 01:52:46.660
[Guest]: know, European monarchy tended to marry with each other, you could see that gene pop up

01:52:46.660 --> 01:52:52.580
[Guest]: across many families. But I think the most impactful was in the Russian monarchy case.

01:52:52.580 --> 01:52:59.340
[Guest]: So Zarina Alexandra was related to Victoria, she was Victoria's granddaughter, and so was

01:52:59.340 --> 01:53:05.860
[Guest]: also a carrier for hemophilia. And she was very worried that her son Alexei would also

01:53:05.860 --> 01:53:10.580
[Guest]: have hemophilia. He actually did have signs of suffering from hemophilia. And it was a

01:53:10.580 --> 01:53:16.580
[Guest]: constant worry over Alexei's future that brought her closer to Rasputin. Because Rasputin came

01:53:16.580 --> 01:53:23.740
[Guest]: and said that he could cure Alexei. And all of that muddle obviously contributed to the

01:53:23.740 --> 01:53:28.660
[Guest]: Tsar's way of dealing with Russia. I mean, he had other problems as well. But all of

01:53:28.660 --> 01:53:36.500
[Guest]: that kind of catalyzed the revolution that saw the Tsar's end, which, I mean, how hemophilia

01:53:36.500 --> 01:53:43.260
[Guest]: can ruin families is, is amazing. And the way it actually figures along European lines

01:53:43.260 --> 01:53:48.860
[Amit Varma]: is, is fascinating to me. And Rasputin, I guess, was a Baba Ramdev of Russia, and fascinating

01:53:48.860 --> 01:53:54.460
[Amit Varma]: description of and this is really unintended consequences where, you know, a genetic mutation

01:53:54.460 --> 01:53:59.820
[Amit Varma]: leads to boom communism. Yeah, Lord help us. Yeah. Now tell me about the caste system.

01:53:59.820 --> 01:54:05.180
[Guest]: Yeah. So obviously, we have been practicing endogamy for many for more than 2000 years

01:54:05.180 --> 01:54:12.100
[Guest]: now. The direct result of this is that if my ancestor from 2000 years ago had a mutation

01:54:12.100 --> 01:54:18.100
[Guest]: that caused a disease, it continues to be perpetuated, simply because there is no new

01:54:18.100 --> 01:54:22.460
[Guest]: gene pools that are coming in, right. And so you see a lot of these founder mutations

01:54:22.460 --> 01:54:26.660
[Guest]: persisting in communities. The most commonly cited one, the most interesting one is in

01:54:26.660 --> 01:54:31.700
[Guest]: the Vaishya community of Andhra Pradesh. So they have a mutation in a gene that prevents

01:54:31.700 --> 01:54:39.220
[Guest]: them from metabolizing certain kinds of anesthesia. So what doctors are seeing is that if you

01:54:39.220 --> 01:54:43.020
[Guest]: give the anesthetic to the patient, the patient dies, doesn't come out of sleep. And then

01:54:43.020 --> 01:54:46.700
[Guest]: some back reasons, they figured out that it was in this particular community only that

01:54:46.700 --> 01:54:51.180
[Guest]: this was happening. And then they traced it back to the mutation that was common to the

01:54:51.180 --> 01:54:55.060
[Guest]: community. So now in Andhra Pradesh, they will ask first, which community belong to

01:54:55.060 --> 01:54:58.660
[Guest]: and if you belong to the Vaishya community, they will give you a different kind of anesthetic

01:54:58.660 --> 01:55:03.340
[Guest]: so that it doesn't kill you. So India has now embarked on projects to try and figure

01:55:03.340 --> 01:55:09.740
[Guest]: out what kind of founder mutations are present. We have, I think, about 5,000 sub-populations,

01:55:09.740 --> 01:55:14.660
[Guest]: if you look purely at genetics. To try and figure out what some populations might be

01:55:14.660 --> 01:55:19.940
[Guest]: more predisposed to what kind of diseases, so that they're at least self-aware and they

01:55:19.940 --> 01:55:27.060
[Guest]: can take proper healthy steps to either prevent the birth of children with diseases or preferably

01:55:27.060 --> 01:55:31.860
[Guest]: marry outside their community. But that is actually a very interesting thing. And I think

01:55:31.860 --> 01:55:38.140
[Guest]: because I have two cousins who are of eligible marriage age, right? Both are extremely well

01:55:38.140 --> 01:55:43.180
[Guest]: educated, one's a doctor, one's a dentist. And obviously, when the family decided that

01:55:43.180 --> 01:55:47.900
[Guest]: they should get married, they started looking within the community. And I understand that,

01:55:47.900 --> 01:55:51.060
[Guest]: you know, at a day to day level, you'd prefer to marry someone from your community because

01:55:51.060 --> 01:55:54.380
[Guest]: you will probably eat a similar kind of food, you're grown up with similar kind of values

01:55:54.380 --> 01:55:58.900
[Guest]: and all of that. But then came that entire, so the girls are like, nah, I don't want to

01:55:58.900 --> 01:56:03.060
[Guest]: get married within this community. I want to find someone outside. Then came the question

01:56:03.060 --> 01:56:07.700
[Guest]: of gothra, right? And elders in my family were like, nah, nah, it makes no sense. You

01:56:07.700 --> 01:56:11.140
[Guest]: know, you should marry within the community as long as not in your gothra. Genes doesn't

01:56:11.140 --> 01:56:14.900
[Guest]: make any problem. So, I mean, these are both extremely well educated girls, like they're

01:56:14.900 --> 01:56:19.380
[Guest]: like, no, no, but you have been doing endogamy for so long. I want healthy children. I want

01:56:19.380 --> 01:56:24.780
[Guest]: bigger gene pool. And the elders are like, no, no, you marry outside gothra, you're fine.

01:56:24.780 --> 01:56:30.660
[Guest]: The entire system of gothra, however, discounts for the fact that once a woman marries, her

01:56:30.660 --> 01:56:38.580
[Guest]: gothra changes, but her genes don't. So, it makes no sense, really. I mean, I can't marry

01:56:38.580 --> 01:56:43.340
[Guest]: my aunt's child because we still have the similar amount of DNA shared as I would with

01:56:43.340 --> 01:56:48.620
[Guest]: an uncle's child. And so, I think a lot of the genetic diseases that we've seen in families,

01:56:48.620 --> 01:56:53.660
[Guest]: in close group families, probably because of the remnant of that is the fact that we

01:56:53.660 --> 01:56:59.380
[Guest]: have automatically assigned different gothras to girls. So, marriage is where sexist behaviour

01:56:59.380 --> 01:57:05.140
[Guest]: actually also transcended into genetic disabilities. But it is...

01:57:05.140 --> 01:57:09.900
[Amit Varma]: This is actually an eye opening TIL for me, and I'm sure for many of my listeners to learn

01:57:09.900 --> 01:57:14.900
[Amit Varma]: that so many physical ailments could have their root cause in a social disease, the

01:57:14.900 --> 01:57:20.080
[Amit Varma]: social disease of caste. And which is, you know, another illustration of why diversity

01:57:20.080 --> 01:57:23.660
[Guest]: is just a bloody good thing. Yeah, but on the other extreme now, we have

01:57:23.660 --> 01:57:28.580
[Guest]: seen these things like Genome Pathari, like, where you can match your DNA and find a compatible

01:57:28.580 --> 01:57:33.700
[Guest]: DNA partner. We still don't know the science behind a lot of this, right? There are some

01:57:33.700 --> 01:57:39.300
[Guest]: extremely encouraging cases such as the Dor Yeshoram, which is a Jewish non-government

01:57:39.300 --> 01:57:44.860
[Guest]: organisation based in the US. The Jewish obviously also have been practising endogamy for a long

01:57:44.860 --> 01:57:49.580
[Guest]: time, at least certain communities have been. And so, what Dor Yeshoram does is that it

01:57:49.580 --> 01:57:55.420
[Guest]: looks at specific diseases that are common to those communities. And it takes DNA samples

01:57:55.420 --> 01:58:00.260
[Guest]: from teenagers, it takes no other information, no name, number, nothing. They will give you

01:58:00.260 --> 01:58:04.020
[Guest]: a unique ID, they'll take your blood sample, and they will just keep it on file. They don't

01:58:04.020 --> 01:58:07.820
[Guest]: even tell you whether you're susceptible to diseases or not. When you choose to marry

01:58:07.820 --> 01:58:12.020
[Guest]: somebody else from your community, you dial in both of your numbers, and they will tell

01:58:12.020 --> 01:58:16.380
[Guest]: you whether it's a compatible match or not. Right, so whether both of you have similar

01:58:16.380 --> 01:58:21.380
[Guest]: diseases or not. That's it. It allows you the right to privacy, they don't take any

01:58:21.380 --> 01:58:26.380
[Guest]: public information. It affords you the right to not know because if you know that you might

01:58:26.380 --> 01:58:31.440
[Guest]: be susceptible to something, but you're never going to have it, it might just end up taking

01:58:31.440 --> 01:58:35.700
[Guest]: steps that you don't need to, right? It might change your lifestyle in a way that you really

01:58:35.700 --> 01:58:39.960
[Guest]: don't require. So, that I think is a really good model. But we just don't know enough

01:58:39.960 --> 01:58:46.260
[Guest]: information about the Indian genome and predisposition to diseases in India to be able to make compatible

01:58:46.260 --> 01:58:51.100
[Guest]: matches yet. So, if someone does come along and asks you for a DNA sample, and they find

01:58:51.100 --> 01:58:58.740
[Guest]: you a match, might not buy in immediately. It is probably just as similar as a patrika.

01:58:58.740 --> 01:59:02.940
[Amit Varma]: But one day when the science is settled, it'll be a better way to do that than a patrika.

01:59:02.940 --> 01:59:08.860
[Amit Varma]: Though ideally, you should go for a date and have a cup of coffee and ask your... Have

01:59:08.860 --> 01:59:14.580
[Amit Varma]: carbs. Have no carbs. Okay, so we have come to almost the end of the time that you've

01:59:14.580 --> 01:59:19.860
[Amit Varma]: so generously agreed to spend in the studio. Before we go, you know, I'll ask you to look

01:59:19.860 --> 01:59:22.940
[Amit Varma]: ahead in the future, you know, you know, the science, you know, the policy environment,

01:59:22.940 --> 01:59:28.020
[Amit Varma]: you know, what's going on, look 20 years ahead, okay, 20 years ahead, and tell me what is

01:59:28.020 --> 01:59:32.220
[Amit Varma]: the best case scenario for humans and what is the worst case scenario with regard to

01:59:32.220 --> 01:59:37.420
[Amit Varma]: where genetic technologies, our knowledge of genetics is taking us because my sense

01:59:37.420 --> 01:59:41.980
[Amit Varma]: is and I think you'll agree with me is that this will be enormously consequential and

01:59:41.980 --> 01:59:46.820
[Amit Varma]: will have huge impact on human welfare. So give me a best case scenario and a worst case.

01:59:46.820 --> 01:59:52.020
[Guest]: My worst case scenario, which I'm tending to think is also the likely scenario, is that

01:59:52.020 --> 01:59:59.940
[Guest]: we selfishly use gene editing to change the nature around us for it to fit with us rather

01:59:59.940 --> 02:00:06.180
[Guest]: than for us to fit with nature. We have picked a handful of species that we want to survive,

02:00:06.180 --> 02:00:10.940
[Guest]: and we basically are going to end up destroying Earth doing that. Best case scenario is that

02:00:10.940 --> 02:00:16.500
[Guest]: we keep the tools ready for when we need to use them. And we can intelligently figure

02:00:16.500 --> 02:00:22.340
[Guest]: out what are the cases in which we really, really need to use this technology and cases

02:00:22.340 --> 02:00:27.460
[Guest]: where our existing technology or a change of our own convenience is enough to guarantee

02:00:27.460 --> 02:00:31.900
[Guest]: a better future. If we can figure out that gene editing is not going to be the one all

02:00:31.900 --> 02:00:37.980
[Guest]: solution that we are ready to give up some comforts to say real and climate change. And

02:00:37.980 --> 02:00:45.060
[Guest]: we opt to do that for our future generations. Then I see in 20 years, we are in a really

02:00:45.060 --> 02:00:52.260
[Guest]: good place on Earth, where we can leave to future generations with the hope that they

02:00:52.260 --> 02:00:53.260
[Guest]: can continue surviving.

